<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Slams EU for Discriminative Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today accused the
European Union (EU) of taking a discriminative attitude towards
Ankara' EU membership issue.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly press briefing here, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Necati Utkan said that the EU's Luxembourg summit failed
to evaluate Turkey's application in the same framework as other
candidate countries.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-EU relationship can not gain a constructive
development unless the latter changes its stand, Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the EU to create a positive negotiation environment
which is beneficial to both sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit meeting, which wound up last Saturday, excluded
Turkey from the present EU enlargement process on grounds that
Turkey did not meet the standards of the European bloc.
</P>
<P>
This decision dealt a heavy blow to Turkey, which has been
making efforts for full EU membership. But so far no substantial
progress has been made due to its differences with the European
body on several issues.
</P>
<P>
Utkan said that the EU should display its virtue of not
insisting on the erroneous and harmful part that it has played so
far.
</P>
<P>
"The EU community in which Turkey will not have a place would
be one which defines and limits itself on the basis of
discrimination and intolerance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman also affirmed that Turkey will
maintain its will of seeking integration with the EU bloc
despite the position laid out at the Luxembourg summit.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said Sunday that
"the EU will never be addressed in any political negotiations,
but our bilateral relations with the EU states will continue."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Ankara can not afford to completely
freeze its ties with the EU, a major trade partner, although it
had suffered a severe setback in its membership bid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
