<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD: Asia Economy Slows Down Overall in Second Half 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report said that a certain number of Asian countries,
notably Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines, will inevitably
carry out economic adjustments in 1998 and 1999. But these
readjustments would tend to be less difficult than those of
Mexico, which experienced a financial crisis at the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
It said that the deficits and foreign debts in percentages of
the GDPs of Southeast Asian countries are smaller than those of
Mexico at that time, while savings still stay at high levels in
these countries.
</P>
<P>
Thailand should make the biggest economic readjustments and it
will continue to register negative economic growth in 1998, while
Malaysia and the Philippines could recover their economic growth
rhythm sooner than Thailand, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Southeast Asian countries can begin to experience
accelerated expansion principally due to improved competitiveness
of their exports following the depreciation of their currencies,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, China, Singapore, Chinese Taiwan, and Hong
Kong of China will see the competitiveness of their exports
"degrade" in the face of those of the countries whose currencies
have depreciated.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance of the parity between the Hong Kong dollar and
the U.S. dollar will inevitably bring about adjustments in Hong
Kong, which will result in a slow-down of its economy in 1998
prior to a new moderate acceleration of growth in 1999, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
In China, a soft touchdown landing of the economy should
continue in 1998 and 1999, while the macro-economic policy of the
country will have a restrictive orientation, it said.
</P>
<P>
The balance of economic operations in China will remain stable
in 1998 and 1999, while inflation will be kept at a relatively low
level mainly thanks to the structural reforms and stabilization
programs, said the report.
</P>
<P>
But the acceleration of reform in the sector of state
enterprises will bring about massive lay-offs and could aggravate
the problem of unemployment in urban areas, if the creation of
jobs don't accelerate greatly in other sectors, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
