<HEADLINE> South Korea's Stock, Currency Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's stock prices and
the won currency rebounded sharply Monday as the government began
to inject funds into financial institutions, and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) showed its intention of advancing loans to the
financially-troubled country.
</P>
<P>
The leading Composite Stock Price Index rose 25.98 points to
385.80, with the trading volume and turnover went up to 79.94
million shares and 459.29 billion won (about 277.49 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Monday also saw the won rally to 1,563.9 against the dollar
around 4 p.m., compared with 1,737.6 won per dollar at Friday's
close.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the dollar hit a day's bottom since
daily permissible fluctuation was expanded from 2.25 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Korea Monday announced a current account
surplus of 600 million dollars in November, the first surplus
since December 1993 when it stood at 560 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a sharp drop in imports resulting from the falling
won against the dollar, South Korea's current account balance
shifted from a deficit of 680 million dollars in October to a
surplus of 600 million dollars in November, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here believe that the worst is over for South
Korea's financial crisis and the country's financial market has
begun to regain stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
