<HEADLINE> UN Inspection Continues in Iraq Amid Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. arms inspection team
continued their mission today with seven groups searching 13
Iraqi sites, according to the official Iraqi news agency.
</P>
<P>
Hussam Mohammed Ameen, director general of the National
Monitoring Department, the Iraqi counterpart of UNSCOM, said the
inspections had been carried out smoothly with full cooperation
from their Iraqi counterparts at the sites.
</P>
<P>
He said the biological team of UNSCOM, the United Nations
Special Commission on eliminating Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction, ended its mission today and left Iraq heading for
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, high-level talks between UNSCOM head Richard Butler
and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz is under way in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Butler and Aziz attended Sunday evening's technical talks, in
which, according to Butler, Aziz said he would give a fuller
report on the biological areas. But neither sides commented on the
talks today.
</P>
<P>
From 10 am today, Butler and Aziz entered into policy level
talks, during which they would discuss the issue of arms
inspectors' access to Iraq's sensitive sites, including
presidential palaces, which Iraq has declared off-limits for
concerns of national security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
A UNSCOM spokesman today Xinhua that "the talks have been
conducted in professional manner," and refused elaboration. Butler
was here seeking unrestricted access for U.N. arms inspectors to
suspected weapons sites in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Butler and Aziz would continue
talks from 7:30 this evening, and Butler would on Thursday report
to the Security Council on the results of his visit to Iraq which
began from last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
