<HEADLINE> France Sales Mirages To UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- France today clinched a
two-billion-dollar-worth military deal with the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) on exporting 35 Mirage 9-2000s in the coming three
years, French President Jacques Chirac announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, the visiting
French president said the contract was signed here today and
France will provide 35 Mirage 9-2000s, a new generation of the
Mirage 5-2000s, to the UAE air force from 1998 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
The warplane deal is worth some 2 billion U.S. dollars, Chirac
said.
</P>
<P>
He gave no further details, but an informed source close to
the French Embassy here said that the deal is part of an ambitious
warplane-purchase package by the UAE.
</P>
<P>
To beef up its air forces, the UAE now is busy conducting
negotiations with U.S. and French aircraft makers on buying 80
combat planes.
</P>
<P>
Chirac disclosed that besides the Mirage deal, his country is
also in talks with Abu Dhabi on exporting Raffle, another
France-made fighter and said the two sides' "cooperation" in this
matter is "considerable."
</P>
<P>
Chirac stressed France's "special, long-standing and solid"
relationship with the UAE and hoped the two countries will further
develop such relationship to set up "true partnership."
</P>
<P>
France signed with the tiny Gulf country a defense agreement in
1995 to boost military cooperation. Chirac said that during his
visit, the two countries have agreed to "make amendments" to the
agreement, but he gave no details.
</P>
<P>
Chirac arrived here Monday night, accompanied by Defense
Minister Alain Richard, Secretary of State in charge of Industry
Christian Pierret and other top officials from major French
companies active in the military, technical and energy sectors.
</P>
<P>
He and his delegation flew home tonight after winding up the
two-day visit to the Gulf country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
