<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Forest Caught Fires in 1997: WWF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- More forest burned down across
the world in 1997 than at any other time in recorded history, the
World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"1997 will be remembered as the year the world caught fire",
said Jean-Paul Jeanrenaud, head of the Forest program of WWF, at a
press conference on WWF's new report of world forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The report, which is released today, states that fires in
Indonesia and Brazil alone have already burned five million
hectares of forests and other land, an area greater than
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
WWF is currently carrying out a study to assess the economic
impacts of Indonesia's fires. Preliminary estimates put the costs
at over 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
New figures also show that in Brazil, forest fires have
increased by more than 50 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although the fires in Indonesia grabbed the headlines, largely
unreported forest fires have raged on every continent, said
Jean-Paul Jeanrenaud.
</P>
<P>
According to WWF's report, large-scale fires also destroyed
vast areas in countries which include Papua New Guinea, Russia,
Colombia, Peru, Tanzania, Kenya, Rwanda, Congo and Australia.
</P>
<P>
As the latest country hit by forest fires, Australia in
December has reported 400 fires raging along its east coast.
</P>
<P>
After examining the causes of the fires, the report reveals
that majority of them are started deliberately and often
illegally, either to clear land for planting, to cover up illegal
logging or to open land for development.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been worsened in some countries by the El
Nino weather event, which has caused prolonged drought, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New License Plate to Help Prevent Bicycle Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- With a casual glance, police
could spot a possible stolen bicycle among thousands rushing by
him.
</P>
<P>
This will become a reality in China, home to 450 million
bicycles, if a new license plate is widely adopted by March 1,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Chinese police say the new license plate has a detachable
middle part which can be taken with the owner. The middle part
must be replaced, police say, or the rider might be mistakenly
treated as a thief.
</P>
<P>
Cui Ziqiu, deputy director of the Public Order Department of
the Ministry of Public Security, revealed here today that "police
authorities regard the new license plate as a new weapon in its
crackdown against bicycle thefts."
</P>
<P>
He said that "the widespread adoption of the new plate is a
prerequisite for the scientific and standardized management of
bicycles."
</P>
<P>
The deputy director explained that the plate should be
prominently fixed on the front part of the bicycle, so traffic
police can spot possible thieves.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Security has issued a notice that, in
addition to experimental regions, most Chinese cities plan to
begin the practice on March 1. Beginning then, all bicycle owners
are required to equip their bikes with this kind of license plate.
</P>
<P>
After June 1, 1999, bicycles without a proper plate cannot be
ridden in urban areas across the country, the notice says.
</P>
<P>
Cui says the experimental regions have shown that the adoption
of the new plate is effective in combating bicycle thefts.
</P>
<P>
Local police stations across the country should be responsible
for the successful implementation of the notice, he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
