<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three NATO Prospects Sign Accession Protocols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organisation (NATO) foreign ministers and their counterparts from
the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland signed the protocols
Tuesday of accession to the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Secretary General, Javier Solana, said at the
ceremony that the signing set the tone for the western military
alliance for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
It is the fourth NATO expansion in its 48-year history. Greece,
Germany and Spain joined NATO in the previous three accession
moves.
</P>
<P>
The signed protocols will first be ratified by the parliaments
of the 16 NATO member states early next year and will then be
ratified by the parliaments of the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Poland prior to April 1999 when the trio can expect to become full
members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
