<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   France Stresses Need to Keep NATO Force in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- France today stressed the need
to keep a NATO military force in Bosnia after the departure of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organisation's Stabilization Force in June
1998.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said at the NATO foreign
ministers' meeting in Brussels that the implementation of the
Dayton peace agreements calls for the presence of a NATO force in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new force in Bosnia should take up several
tasks, including the dissuasion of any inclination toward the
resurgence of violence, ensuring the surveillance of some very
sensitive zones such as Mostar and Brcko, controlling the
activities of the military forces of all sides and supporting the
civilian part of the Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
The NATO foreign ministers today launched a plan in Brussels on
the sending of a new follow-up force to Bosnia after the
expiration of the mission of the Stabilization Force (SFOR), said
reports from Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The new force should consist of European and American forces
sharing tasks and risks in the field, said Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
The NATO asked the military officers of its member countries to
work on four options presented by the United States on the new
force and submit a report by mid-January for final approval.
</P>
<P>
The options are: a total withdrawal of SFOR, a mission of
dissuasion on a reduced scale by SFOR to be enforced by the NATO
soldiers serving in SFOR in the field, a mission of dissuasion to
be reinforced with additional forces from NATO, and maintenance of
the equivalant of the SFOR force, which consist of 30,000
soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
