<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Public Enthusiastic About Private Investment(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese are becoming more
enthusiastic about investing, something that has been helped by
the prospect of good returns as the country moves to put more free
capital into its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
A recent report on urban investment by the Beijing Lingdian
(Zero) Survey Company shows that China is entering a period of
public investment.
</P>
<P>
Of the residents in five cities surveyed, 69.5 percent have
savings deposits, 20.9 percent invest in bonds, 20.8 percent buy
securities, and 12.3 percent invest in life insurance or other
social security systems. Others prefer collecting curiosities or
direct investment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The market economy has considerably expanded investment areas
for people at large and, more importantly, urbanites have large
amounts of extra money to invest.
</P>
<P>
By the first half of this year, savings deposits in China's
banks totaled more than 7.5 trillion yuan. Of that total, 4.2
trillion was from urban residents who still had 600 billion yuan
in cash on hand as well as 30 billion U.S. dollars in banks,
according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
On Oct. 23, China's central bank reduced interest rates on
loans and savings deposits for the third time since last year. An
increasing number of urbanites have begun to withdraw their money
from banks and have turned to other high-paying investment
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Poor Nutrition Threatens Health of World's Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Malnutrition contributes to
the death of nearly seven million children in the world each year,
more than deaths from any infectious disease, war or natural
disaster, according to a report released here today by the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
When it does not kill, malnutrition can leave victims maimed,
intellectually impaired and suffering from a weakened immune
system, according to the 1998 State of the World's Children Report
of UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
The overall number of malnourished children is on the rise,
despite reductions in malnutrition in some parts of the world,
said UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, among the 12 million children 5 years old
and younger in developing countries who died of some avoidable
causes, half are related to malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
In China, poor sanitation and improper breast-feeding practices
result in the deaths of thousands of newborns each year. A report
on the state of Chinese children in the 1990s shows that 15.8
percent of the country's children under 5 suffered from middle and
high levels of malnutrition. In poor areas, more girls suffer from
malnutrition than boys, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Micronutrient deficiencies such as iodine disorders and iron
deficiency anemia exist broadly in China, said Keshab B. Mathema,
UNICEF's area representative for China and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Unless the Chinese government takes appropriate remedial
measures, the economic impact of poor nutrition will still be
considerable for China in terms of lost productivity and higher
health care expenses for illnesses related to malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
"Good nutrition is not just a matter of adequate food," said
Bellamy. "It requires nutritious food, good health care and
appropriate care of pregnant women and children."
</P>
<P>
Undernourished women who become pregnant give birth to children
who are also malnourished and whose ability to contribute to
society is diminished, she said.
</P>
<P>
She urged governments in poor and rich countries to support
actions to combat malnutrition, and warned that the price of
inaction is high -- malnutrition will harm millions of children's
health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Public Enthusiastic About Private Investment(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Private investors have also been looking for better investment
opportunities in recent years. In 1993, foreign exchange
transactions were opened to individuals. Now nine foreign
currencies are available to investors. By the end of June, China's
Bank of Communications Shanghai Branch had had 160 million
U.S. dollars of personal sales and purchases of foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Banks also are making a new effort to provide more service
choices. Last year, the Bank of China's Shenzhen Branch set up the
country's first "private money management center." By opening an
account at the bank, the investor can rely on the center for
personal savings deposits, foreign exchange transactions,
securities purchases and sales.
</P>
<P>
In May, Shanghai Pudong Development Bank opened a personal
finance department to introduce new services for individual
financial transactions, and to provide advice to increase the
value of private assets.
</P>
<P>
China's economic restructuring, the commercialization of banks
and the establishment of modern enterprise system require a
greater influx of public funds. This also has increased investment
channels for personal investors.
</P>
<P>
However, the foundation for increased personal investment lies
in the fact that 40 percent of the country's annual wealth is
saved in banks, said Mao Yushi, director of Beijing's Tianze
Economic Research Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
