<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Development Zones Boost China's Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's high-technology
development zones' total income will reach 500 billion yuan (60
billion U.S. dollars) by 2000, said Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of
the State Science and Technology Commission (SSTC).
</P>
<P>
Xu said at a news conference here today that China's high-tech
development zones, similar to science parks in foreign countries,
are playing an increasingly important role in turning technologies
into a productive force. These zones introduce foreign capital and
advanced technologies, develop new industries and reform
traditional industries.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will focus on the development of products
with national intellectual property rights and encourage the
high-tech industries to enter the world market.
</P>
<P>
Since the country's first national high-tech development zone
was established in Beijing in 1988, 53 have mushroomed in 29
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
This August, the State Council approved Beijing, Suzhou, Hefei
and Xi'an to be China's first science parks open to members of
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the total technological, industrial and
trade income of the high-tech development zones increased to 230
billion yuan (27.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, 26 times greater
than 1991. And the zones earned foreign exchange of 4.3 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, a 36-fold increase over five years ago.
</P>
<P>
So far, 405 high-tech enterprises in the zones have exceeded
100 million yuan each in total output value. And 42 large
enterprises and groups have surpassed 1 billion yuan each in total
output value. They include Founder Group, Legend Computer Group,
Stone Corp., Qingdao Haier Group, Sichuan Changhong Group.
</P>
