<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hang Seng Index To Trace More Red Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Two more China-affiliated
companies, whose shares are known as red chips, will be included
as the constituent stocks of the Hang Seng Index, which tracks the
performance of 33 blue chips listed on the Stock Exchange of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom (HK) Ltd and Shanghai Industrial Holdings Ltd,
will be added to the Hang Seng Index with effect from January 27,
1998, replacing Shun Tak Holdings Ltd and South China Morning Post
(Holdings) Ltd, the HSI Services Limited, the compiler of the
Index, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle would increase the market capitalization coverage
of the Index from 65.9 percent to 71.1 percent as calculated at
November 28 this year, and likewise, raise the turnover coverage
from 47.7 percent to 57 percent for the month of November.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Wong, chairman of the HSI Services Limited, said
today:" With a market capitalization coverage of about 70 percent,
the Hang Seng Index is able to achieve its prime objective of
reflecting the performance of the Hong Kong stock market through a
sample of large capitalization and liquid stocks."
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index usually covers 70 percent of the total
market capitalization, but the proportion has recently dropped to
around 65 percent. The turnover coverage of the Index, usually at
60 percent, also fell to a historic low of 24 percent in August
and rebounded to 47 percent in late November.
</P>
<P>
Wong noted:" The emergence of the red chips and H shares has
led to a structural change in the Hong Kong stock market. The
importance of the red chips and H shares will continue to grow and
cannot be neglected."
</P>
<P>
When the reshuffle takes place in January 1998, there will be
five China-affiliated companies being constituent stocks of the
Hang Seng Index. The other three are CITIC Pacific Ltd, Guangdong
Investment Ltd, and China Resources Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Based on a recent in-depth review, Wong said that there would
be no change to the number of 33 constituent stocks of the Hang
Seng Index.
</P>
<P>
"Being a market capitalization weighted index, the number of
constituent stocks is not the key factor in determining the Hang
Seng Index's ability to accurately track the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The HSI Services Limited also revised its selection criteria
for new constituent stocks, which will no longer be required to
have a substantial business presence in Hong Kong and a listing
history of 24 months. "But they should not be a foreign company as
defined by the SEHK," Wong added.
</P>
<P>
The HSI Services Limited announced today that the new Hang Seng
100 Index will be launched in April 1998, which will cover the top
100 companies in terms of both market capitalization and turnover
on the SEHK.
</P>
<P>
The existing Hang Seng Midcap 50 Index, which was launched in
July 1995 to track the performance of middle capitalization
companies, will be restructured next April to mirror the
performance of the 50 stocks ranked from 101 to 150 in terms of
market capitalization and turnover.
</P>
<P>
HSI Services Limited, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hang Seng
Bank, compiles and manages a series of indices, with the Hang Seng
Index as the key barometer of the Hong Kong economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
