<HEADLINE> Mass AIDS Tests for British Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Mass AIDS tests are being
carried out on soldiers at the Catterick base, Britain's largest
army base.
</P>
<P>
The tests are being undertaken following fears that two local
women have been deliberately infecting soldiers with HIV virus,
said army sources at the base in Yorkshire, northern England.
</P>
<P>
A memo had been circulated at the base, strongly advising
soldiers who had had casual sex with local women to seek medical
advice, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The memo said army officers had received confidential advice
that at least two women in the Catterick area have contracted the
AIDS virus and are HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
"The same females are believed to be liberal with their
affections, particularly to soldiers," it added.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 soldiers had sought medical advice in the past
week, local press reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The garrison normally houses 5,500 military personnel but many
of the troops are currently serving in Bosnia and Northern
Ireland. 
</P>
