<HEADLINE> China to Continue Strategic Readjustments on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China has made new
achievements in restructuring its economy and realized its goals
of the macro-economic control in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The economy has been growing at a moderately rapid speed, while
the inflation has remained at a relatively low level, which has
further improved the country's macro-economic environment and
strengthened its comprehensive power.
</P>
<P>
This was learned from the National Conference on Planning,
which was held here from December 13-16. Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua
attended the meeting and Chen Jinghua, minister of the State
Planning Commission, made a work report to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Conference urged to speed up the economic strategic
restructuring in 1998, in a bid to maintain a good trend of
development.
</P>
<P>
It called to further consolidate the status of agriculture as
the basis of the economy by speeding up the industrialization of
the sector, increasing investment, stepping up efforts to improve
ecological environment for farming, continue carrying out the
reform on grain marketing system.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also urged to further open up the economic sector
to the outside world by encouraging to introduce more advanced
technology and equipment, and exploring the international market.
</P>
<P>
The issue of re-employment should be given priority, while more
small towns should be set up so as to absorb excessive labor force
in the countryside, the conference said.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to follow the moderately tight financial
and monetary policy and to eliminate any factor that would lead to
inflation and economic fluctuation in the country, according to
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the meeting, the country will continue
its reforms on planning, financing, investment and pricing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
