<HEADLINE> Most Guangzhou Workers Take Part-time Vocational Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A recent sample survey
showed that over 60 percent of Guangzhou's workers take vocational
courses in their spare time.
</P>
<P>
With the reform of employment, more and more workers in the
southern coastal city have changed their concept of "life-long
employment" -- a practice in the past planned economy. China is
now practicing a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Workers organized book-reading societies, knowledge
competition and symposiums for themselves.
</P>
<P>
In addition, concerned governmental departments supported
various vocational courses for in-service workers and
layoffs. More than 20,000 laid-off workers, who are about 45 years
old, have had the opportunity to learn more skills and found new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
The city's young workers also favor self-study programs to
improve their educational level.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in a period between January and October,
educational expenditure for each worker averaged nearly 400 yuan
(about 48 US dollars), increasing by 16 percent over the same 1996
period. 
