<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Malnutrition the Major Cause of Child Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Malnutrition leads to the
deaths of nearly seven million children a year, more than any
infectious disease, war or natural disaster, says a report
released here today by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
Where it does not kill, malnutrition can leave victims
physically maimed, intellectually impaired and suffering from the
consequences of a weakened immune systems, said the report called
the "1998 State of the World's Children Report".
</P>
<P>
While there have been dramatic reductions in malnutrition in
some parts of the world, the report said, the overall number of
malnourished children is rising.
</P>
<P>
No less than half of all children under the age of five in
South Asia, and one-third of those in sub-Saharan Africa, as well
as millions of children in industrialized countries, are
malnourished.
</P>
<P>
Starvation of the kind arising from famines, war and other
catastrophes, although much covered by world media, is responsible
for only a tiny part of the worldwide nutrition crisis, the report
points out.
</P>
<P>
Studies show that deaths from diarrhoea can be reduced by 35 to
40 percent if children are given vitamin A supplements.
</P>
<P>
Other research shows that vitamin A could halve the number of
deaths among children suffering from measles. Vitamin A, is found
in such foods as eggs, butter, whole milk and liver.
</P>
<P>
Supplements of vitamin A and zinc may boost children's
resistance to malaria, which currently kills 600,000 young
children each year. Moreover, zinc supplements seem to have a
remarkable effect in reducing the toll of diarrhoea and pneumonia
cases in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the lives of at least 300,000 young children were
saved by vitamin A supplement programs in developing countries,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Over 35 countries now routinely provide vitamin A supplements
with immunizations or as part of health campaigns. UNICEF
estimates that more than half of all young children, in countries
where vitamin A deficiency is known to be common, received vitamin
A capsules in 1996, compared to about one-third in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC National Conference Opens in Mafikeng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAFIKENG, South Africa, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The 50th
National Conference of South Africa's ruling African National
Congress opened today in sweltering heat in Mafikeng, capital of
North-West Province.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, outgoing ANC President Nelson Mandela
defended his party's policy and fought back at criticisms of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
He listed the achievements of his government in the three and
half years since 1994, saying that the oppressed majority now
have access to houses, water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the media and opposition parties' criticisms of
the ANC's failure to fulfill some of its election promises in
1994.
</P>
<P>
"We have succeeded to maintain the unity and territorial
integrity of the country, having guaranteed against any serious
tendency towards Balkanization," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country marched out of international isolation
after the 1994 election and South Africa's relations with the
rest of the world were developing well.
</P>
<P>
"During the period, we have also succeeded to resolve such
difficult problems in our international affairs as our relations
with the People's Republic of China."
</P>
<P>
Mandela declared last year that his country would sever ties
with Taiwan and recognize the People's Republic of China. The two
countries are expected to establish diplomatic relations by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Mandela also noted his country's contribution
to the settlement of conflicts on the African continent and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
Mandela counter-attacked the media and opposition on the
question of crime. He said: "The propaganda the government and
police are doing nothing is entirely without substance."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated firmly that his government would not
reintroduce the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
The five-day gathering of more than 3,000 delegates from the
country's all nine provinces is expected to go down in ANC's
75-year history as one of the most important conferences.
</P>
<P>
Crucial policies, such as the macro-economic strategy, are
expected to be discussed and designed to take the ANC to the 1999
general election and the country to the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki is to step
into Mandela's shoes as party chief and in 1999, he is expected
to become the second black president of the country.
</P>
<P>
ANC National Chairman Jacob Zuma is the only candidate to be
Mbeki's deputy although he faces challenge from Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Madikizela-Mandela was not among the list of nominations for
the top six positions of the ANC, but she still has a chance to
vie for the powerful post through direct nominations from the
floor.
</P>
<P>
The post of the new ANC secretary-general is expected to go to
Kgalema Motlanthe, currently general secretary of the National
Union of Mineworkers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
