<HEADLINE> 1997 a Year of Progress, Says NATO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organisation (NATO) Secretary General Javier Solana Tuesday
described 1997 as a truly remarkable year in the history of the
military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the beginning of the North Atlantic Council at
foreign ministerial level, Solana said that meetings held earlier
this year had laid the foundation of an inwardly and outwardly
renewed NATO.
</P>
<P>
"The new NATO is ready to meet the challenges of the 21st
century," he said as NATO foreign ministers gathered to discuss
options for follow-on forces in Bosnia after the United Nations
mandate expires next June.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance has to make its decision before
next March 1 over follow-on forces, or on a complete withdrawal
from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda of the foreign minister meeting are NATO's
internal and external adaptations such as the new command
structure, the Combined Joint Task Force and the European Security
and Defense Identity.
</P>
<P>
Later today, NATO foreign ministers are scheduled to sign the
accession protocols of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
before the protocols go through the ratification process in the
parliaments of the 16 NATO member states early next year.
</P>
<P>
The protocols will then be ratified by the parliaments of the
three eastern European countries prior to April 1999 when the trio
can expect to become full members of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief also described the alliance's relationship with
Russia and Ukraine as having been put on a new cooperative basis,
and the creation of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council as
providing a political framework for wide-spread partnership
activities.
</P>
<P>
The NATO foreign ministers will also meet their counterparts
from Ukraine and Russia during the two-day meeting. Such issues as
nuclear transparency and military strategy toward each other are
expected to be discussed between the former Cold War foes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
