<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Launch Nationwide Aid-The-Needy Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- An aid-the-needy drive was
launched here today by the All China Federation of Trade Unions
(ACFTU) to ensure that "every worker's family has a good New
Year's holiday and a good Spring Festival."
</P>
<P>
The annual drive is part of the traditional "send-warmth
project" sponsored for years by the ACFTU, which focuses on
helping needy workers.
</P>
<P>
During the months around the two holidays, said Ni Haomei,
ACFTU vice chairperson and spokeswoman, the ACFTU will send 10
teams across the country to visit some of the needy workers. The
teams also will inspect local work relating to the "send-warmth
project," including establishment of a special fund for the
project and creation of files on needy workers, most of whom have
been laid off.
</P>
<P>
About 460 city trade unions, 2,100 county ones, and 150,000
grassroots groups have set up files on needy workers, Ni said, and
the total amount of "send-warmth" funds across the country has
reached 2 billion yuan (240 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"With a growing number of state-owned enterprises plagued by
sluggish business, helping laid-off workers find new jobs has
become an increasingly important part of the 'send-warmth
project,'" said Chen Zhigang, an ACFTU official in charge of
social security for workers.
</P>
<P>
There are about 11 million laid-off workers across China,
accounting for one tenth of the total employed, according to
figures released by the ACFTU.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the fund for this year's send-warmth drive, estimated
at several million yuan, primarily will go to the areas with the
largest number of laid-off workers -- northeast, northwest and
central China.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions throughout China so far have established nearly
500 job agencies and 1,300 job training facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
