<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Movie "Seven Years in Tibet" Distorts History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The movie "Seven Years
in Tibet" distorts historical events and is based on invented
stories, a Tibetan scholar said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the movie at a press conference, Dotar, a
researcher at the China Tibetology Center, said "It distorts
history and historical events and portraits an untruthful picture
of the Tibetan natural environment."
</P>
<P>
"It is really cheap stuff and full of loopholes. I'm especially
irritated by the fact that it prettifies a Nazi while vilifying
Tibetans," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The ignorance of the movie makers is shocking. They seem to
try to cheat their audience."
</P>
<P>
"Tibetans are courageous people who fought a last-ditch battle,
for instance, with the British invaders in 1904," who are quite
different from the description by the movie as cowards, Dotar said.
</P>
<P>
Tibet in the movie was a land of peace, away from turmoil of
the world. But in fact, Dotar said, Tibet in the 1940s was under
serfdom, where feudal lords who constituteed only five percent of
the population possessed 95 percent of the means of production.
</P>
<P>
"They (serfs) were even more miserable than the black slaves in
the United States before the civil war. So Tibet was at that time
not peaceful at all because the struggles between the slaves
and their lords were very fierce," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also gave some other examples in the movie which do not
comply with the facts.
</P>
<P>
The movie, which is based on the leading character's memoir,
tells a story of a Nazi Austrian mountaineer who, in the fall of
1939, escaped from a British prisoner-of-war camp to Lhasa of
Tibet. He later made friends with the young Dalai Lama and became
his English tutor. He stayed there for seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
