<HEADLINE> Kaunda to attend ANC convention in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian former president
Kenneth Kaunda will attend the convention of the African National
Congress (ANC) this week at the invitation of the ruling party of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Information and publicity secretary of the United National
Independence Party (UNIP), Bwendo Mulengela, confirmed the
invitation here today.
</P>
<P>
UNIP leader Kaunda, who had been president of the country for
27 years until 1991, was a strong backer of ANC when it fought a
prolonged fight against apartheid and an old friend of ANC
leader, president Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda went abroad on the eve of the October 28 coup attempt
in his country and has not returned from his marathon trip to
lobby for international pressure on the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia's ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy
(MMD) has also been invited to the convention, at which Mandela
is expected to quit his post as party president as a first step
toward his retirement from active politics. 
</P>
