<HEADLINE> China's Longest Highway Bridge Completed in Wenzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A 17.1-km highway bridge,
China's longest, was completed today in Wenzhou, a booming coastal
city famous for its thriving private sector in east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The Wenzhou Bridge, whose construction started on December 8,
1994 and cost a total of 1.179 billion yuan (about 140 million US
dollars), spans over the Oujiang, a major river in southern
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
With a span of 270 meters over the river, the bridge's land
parts cover an area of over 18 hectares and help link four
counties and districts of Wenzhou.
</P>
<P>
Part of a major expressway across Zhejiang that is under
construction, the bridge, if opened to traffic, will enable
vehicles going to Wenzhou to cut their journey by 45 kilometers.
They used to have to go roundabout for a downstream bridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
