<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chia-Wei Woo and His University (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Professor Woo observed that, located in South China with the
base in Hong Kong, HKUST should emphasize Hong Kong's character
and build on Hong Kong's unique strength.
</P>
<P>
But the "Hong Kong" he refers to is not limited to the 235
islands and one peninsula within the confines of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). He looks farther beyond to
the Pearl River Estuary -- the "backyard" of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To get his idea across, Professor Woo pointed at a map on the
wall of his office: "The estuary can be described as an
equilateral triangle with Shenzhen, Nansha and Zhuhai at its
vertices. The triangle encloses the mouth of the Pearl River."
</P>
<P>
In a few years, a bridge spanning Shenzhen Bay to connect Hong
Kong's western "New Territories" and Shenzhen's Nanshan district
will have been constructed, and so will much-longer Lingdingyang
Bridge linking Hong Kong and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the estuary will resemble the San Francisco Bay
Area of the United States as a metropolis of high finance, high
technology, strong service industries, and environmental beauty.
"Let's call it Hong Kong Bay Area," he ventured.
</P>
<P>
It is in the Hong Kong Bay Area that HKUST is building its home
base, and from the area HKUST will extend its contributions to all
of China, Professor Woo said.
</P>
<P>
It has forges close cooperation with many institutions in the
inland areas. Joint labs have been produced in HKUST with the
Chinese Academy of Sciences for research in such fields as biology
and biotechnology and micro-electronics. Some 250 postgraduates
from the inland areas are studying in HKUST.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chia-Wei Woo and His University (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- In September 1988, Professor
Chia-Wei Woo returned from San Francisco, USA, to Hong Kong and
took up his new position as the founding president of the Hong
Kong University of Science and Technology (HKUST).
</P>
<P>
Giving up the presidency of a major American university, he
took up the challenge of developing a third university in Hong
Kong into a pride for the region.
</P>
<P>
Since then he has witnessed every step made by fledgling HKUST:
the building of the terraced campus on the waterfront of Clear
Water Bay, the international recruitment campaign for top-rank
faculty, the opening of HKUST in October 1991 with the first
intake of 600 students from over 10,000 applicants, and so on.
</P>
<P>
Now "it has been almost six years since the opening of HKUST,
student enrollment has reached full size of 7,000 and our faculty
is very much in place. Teaching, research and service are
advancing right on the track," said the professor of physics.
</P>
<P>
He is very satisfied with the development of the university.
The strength of a university lies in its people, whether or not it
has years-old school buildings is of no significance, he said.
</P>
<P>
To coincide with the university's marching into a consolidation
period, Hong Kong has become an increasingly important economic
center of China with its return to the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Under the new circumstances, Professor Woo is contemplating on
national and international positioning of his university.
</P>
<P>
As of its place in China, Prof. Woo is determined that HKUST
should rank among China's very top universities, this is
particularly the case in the category of research-oriented science
 and technological institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chia-Wei Woo and His University (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Either never do it, or do it best, Professor Woo said, and he
is proud that "each of our departments is a signboard."
</P>
<P>
During the past year, HKUST chose a small number of
interdisciplinary projects and allocated some research
infrastructure money to seed each project.
</P>
<P>
The initial batch of "high impact areas" includes China
business and management, construction and structural engineering
and electronic packaging and assembly.
</P>
<P>
Others will follow: Internet technologies, magnetic materials,
linguistics, ocean science and other fields spread across the
university's four schools.
</P>
<P>
Looking at Hong Kong's tertiary education which has been
largely expanded in past several years, Professor Woo noted, money
spent in education is never an expenditure, but an investment in
the future.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the language, both English and Chinese,
capabilities of university students should be improved, their
vision be broadened and their sense of responsibility for the
community be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
He is a keen advocator of four-year system for Hong Kong's
universities, instead of the existing three-year one, to allow
future graduates a more complete education.
</P>
<P>
As students of newly-inaugurated HKSAR, they should also get a
better understanding of their country, about her history,
geography, people and latest development, and in this regard civic
education is highly in demand, Professor Woo continued.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth congregation at HKUST this November, Professor Woo
told his students: "It must sound unfamiliar to you, our Class of
1997, to be addressed as the first graduates of China's Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology."
</P>
<P>
"But stop and think for a moment. How thrilling it must be --
for each and every one of you -- to mark history in this personal
matter."
</P>
<P>
Woo was born in Shanghai, received secondary education in Hong
Kong and acquired his BS, MA and Ph.D. degrees and postdoctoral
studies in the United States. In 1983, the then 45-year-old Woo
became president of San Francisco State University, the first
Chinese-American to head a major university in the U.S.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chia-Wei Woo and His University (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Looking beyond China, Professor Woo is ambitious to develop
HKUST into a world-class university.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the 16-member Association of East Asian Research
Universities was formally launched, grouping HKUST in Hong Kong
and most eminent universities from the Chinese inland areas,
Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
HKUST expects to strengthen its partnership, within the
framework of the association, with top institutions in the region
which will lead the world economy well into the next century,
Professor Woo said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to being one of East Asia's top research
universities, HKUST must be a world-class university situated at
the cutting edge in all academic and research and development
fields which HKUST selects as "targets of pursuit", he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
"In fields that advance and change rapidly, one's work is
either first-class or without class. No mediocrity can be
tolerated," Professor Woo spoke of his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
"A university of our size must resolve to focus. The number of
specialties must be limited so that each chosen specialty can
achieve a critical mass," he explained.
</P>
<P>
HKUST chose to establish only 19 academic Departments,
including two called Divisions, and each Department limited to no
more than a few specialties selected on the basis of stringent
criteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
