<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Classified Loans in Banks Total 2.34 Bln </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Total classified loans in
Bangladesh's banking sector till September 30 this year stood at
106.69 billion taka (2.34 billion U.S. dollars), according to a
latest estimate made by Bangladesh Bank.
</P>
<P>
The estimate compiled by the central bank recently on the basis
of the reports sent by various banks said that out of the total
classified amount, 13.81 billion taka (304 million dollars) had
been termed as doubtful and 16.14 billion taka (355 million
dollars) as substandard.
</P>
<P>
Out of 39 banks, 37 banks submitted reports to the central
bank, and these reports were compiled on December 9 last year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total credit of 405.59 billion taka (8.91 billion
dollars) disbursed by the banks, 316.28 billion taka (6.95 billion
dollars) remained outstanding. Nearly 130 billion taka (2.86
billion dollars) had been identified as overdue amount.
</P>
<P>
This amount, however, did not include the loans having
outstanding figures below one million taka (22,000 dollars), the
estimate said.
</P>
<P>
In the range of overdue loans, 48.47 billion taka (1.07 billion
dollars) are lying with 164 borrowers who took loans up to 100
million taka and above. Of these 164 borrowers, 137 are private
individuals and different firms whose overdue loans amounted to
28.69 billion taka (631 million dollars) while the 19.78 billion
taka (435 million dollar) overdue credit remained with the public
sector.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's total number of overdue borrowers stands at
13,112, according to the central bank statistics.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has already strengthened its monitoring system
while various commercial banks have taken strict measures to
improve the credit and loan situation in the country, the local
press reported recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
