<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loans to India, Kazakstan, Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Manila-based Asian
Development Bank (ADB) today approved loans to India, Kazakstan
and the Philippines for different projects in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a press release that it would provide 150
million U.S. dollars to help India construct a pipeline system to
transport liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) from the western to the
northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline system offers the least-cost method for
transporting LPG over long distances, improves the reliability of
LPG supply and reduces greenhouse gas emissions, the news release
said.
</P>
<P>
The bank also approved a loan of 100 million U.S. dollars and
technical assistance amounting to 680,000 dollars for a pension
reform program in Kazakstan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippines' power supply would be strengthened
by a power transmission reinforcement project, for which the ADB
agreed to provide a 191.4-million-dollar loan, the news release
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
