<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cabinet Shake-up in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's military
leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma reshuffled his cabinet late
Monday, dropping three cabinet ministers, State Radio and
television reported early this morning.
</P>
<P>
It is the first reshuffle since Koroma seized power on May 25.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers dropped were the Secretary of State for
Internal Affairs, retired Brigade Leslie Lymon, the Secretary of
State for Works, Colonel Saaba Kamara and the Secretary of State
for the East, Captain Edward Kanneh.
</P>
<P>
Chief Secretary of State Captain Solomon Musa retained his
post, and so were Foreign Minister Paolo Bangura, Attorney
General Manley Spaine, Development Secretary Victor Bandon and
Secretary of State for Finance Joe Amara Bangali.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary of State for Trade, Eldred Collins, the number
three man in the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
organization has been moved to the new Ministry of Works, Energy
and Power.
</P>
<P>
A civilian who was Director General of the Department of
Social Welfare, Dr Baila Leigh is now Secretary of State for
Health.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Information has been merged with Tourism and
Culture and it is now headed by a civilian named Kandeh Bangura.
</P>
<P>
a new Ministry of Religious Affairs has been created and
headed by Reverend David Bangura.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor has been renamed Department of
Employment, Industrial Relations, Youth and Social Mobilization
while sports is now Department of Recreational Sports.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Allieu Kamara now becomes Under Secretary
of State for Information.
</P>
<P>
There are 10 civilians in the 24-member cabinet which also
includes four members of the RUF and one woman, Major Kula Samba
who retains the post of Secretary of State for Social Welfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
