<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Crops Loss Predicted in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The unseasonable El Nino
rainfall has caused a loss of 25 percent of unharvested maize and
30 percent of unharvested wheat in Kenya in October and November,
according to the data issued by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Further significant post-harvest losses are anticipated due to
higher than usual moisture content of the harvested crop,
according to the data contained in a report.
</P>
<P>
"National long rains maize output is estimated to be 1.95
million tons as compared to 2.06 million tons in 1996 and a
1991-1996 average of 2.22 million tons," the Daily Nation
newspaper today quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The current losses follow earlier yield losses that had
resulted from two uncharacteristic dry spells in May/June and
September during the crops' critical growing stages," the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that famine and higher food prices will be
experienced next year.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rainfalls in the short rains season this year have
also resulted in severe flooding in the northern and eastern
pastoral areas and claimed lives of human beings and livestock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Reserve Bank Raises Rediscount Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
yesterday raised the rediscount rate by three percentage points,
to 31.5 percent, for the second time in less than a month in
reaction to speculative pressures on the Zimbabwe Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rediscount rate was last increased on November 17 this
year to 28.5 percent as speculative attacks exerted pressures on
the currency.
</P>
<P>
On November 14, the Zimbabwe Dollar fell to its all time low
of 25 Zimbabwe Dollars to the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday the Zimbabwe Dollar fell again to about 19
Zimbabwe Dollars to the U.S. Dollar before stabilizing at around
17 Zimbabwe Dollars to the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Reserve Bank yesterday said only half of
the 160 million U.S. Dollars in corporate foreign currency
accounts ordered liquidated to improve liquidity on the market
had been offloaded.
</P>
<P>
"The outstanding balance still to be offloaded, together with
current holdings of foreign exchange reserves, lines of credit
available to the bank and world bank funds expected to be
disbursed soon, will ensure that the economy has sufficient
reserves of up to three months of import cover," the bank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Bank's Aid Loan to Africa up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Arab bank for Economic
Development in Africa increased its aid to Africa by 12.5 percent
to 5.396 billion Shillings (some 90 million U.S. Dollars) last
year, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figure in the previous year stood at 4.795 billion
Shillings (80 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bank gave top priority to the agricultural sector and
promotion of rural development during the year, in line with its
principle of realizing and maintaining food security on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector received 2.1 billion Shillings (35
million Dollars) in 1996, representing 41.8 percent of the total
allocation.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by the infrastructure sector with 2.069
billion Shillings (34.5 million Dollars) and environment projects
with 420 million Shillings (seven million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Most of the bank's aid loans came from credit financing by
Arab and Non-Arab financing institutions as well as governments
of the beneficiary countries. The interest rates on the loans
was three percent.
</P>
<P>
Sychelles and Malawi were the highest recipients receiving
2.815 billion Shillings (47 million Dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
The bank has issued 42 percent of its total loans, or 32.1
billion Shillings (535 million Dollars) to Africa since it was
launched in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
