<HEADLINE> 70 Admitted to Hospital Due to Cholera in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Seventy patients suffering
from cholera were admitted into a local hospital in Kampala
Monday, officials at the hospital said.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic has already spread to 13 suburbs of the city
within a week, and local health authorities have established
clinics in the disease-hit areas to treat patients.
</P>
<P>
One patient has died of the epidemic so far, and others
admitted in the hospital are recovering, said Lawrence Kaggwa,
the administrator of State Mulago Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Mulago Hospital, the most prestigious medical institution in
the country, will man the makeshift clinics in tents fighting the
epidemic, said "The New Vision" paper.
</P>
<P>
Kihumuro Apuuli, director of medical services, visited Monday
the disease-hit areas with Misaaki Mubiru, the public officer of
Kampala City Council.
</P>
<P>
Among the admitted, 32 are children and suspected to have
infected from their mothers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Both Mubiru and Kaggwa attributed the epidemic to contaminated
water sources caused by consecutive rains in recent weeks that
flooded the drainage in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
