<HEADLINE> Kaunda to Be Back for Zambian Inter-party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian president
Kenneth Kaunda does not need safety guarantee to return home and
will come back from his marathon overseas trip to attend the
proposed inter-party dialogue, his aide has said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Kaunda's press aide Muhabi Lungu
as saying here Monday that information chief of the United
National Independence Party (UNIP), Bwendo Mulengela, may have
been expressing a personal opinion when he said last week that
Kaunda needs assurance from the government.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda will soon return to attend the inter-party dialogue
scheduled for next month, said Lungu who returned home at the
weekend after a tour with Kaunda which took them to Britain, the
United States, India ans South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Micheal Sata, national secretary of the ruling Movement for
Multi-party Democracy (MMD) said last Sunday that Kaunda is not a
party and his absence will not be allowed to affect the
time-table for the crucial talks.
</P>
<P>
Sata was reacting to a statement issued by Kaunda's UNIP
earlier last week that Kaunda, who went abroad on the eve of the
October 28 coup attempt, will attend the inter-party talks if
only the government guarantees his safe return.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, detained Zambia Democratic Congress President Dean
Mung'omba has give his party the go-ahead to represent him at the
inter-party talks.
</P>
<P>
Mung'omba was detained for alleged involvement in the coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
