<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Engine Failure Crashes Tajik Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A UAE aviation official
said today that initial investigations showed Monday's Tajik plane
crash near the UAE city Sharjah was caused by an engine failure.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Abdullah bin Mohammed al Thani, chairman of Sharjah's
Civil Aviation Authority told a press conference in Sharjah held
this morning that the digital flight data recorder, commonly known
as the black box and the cockpit voice recorder were recovered
hours after the accident.
</P>
<P>
Through the initial studies, Mohammed said that the crash, in
which 85 Tajik passengers and crew members were killed and one
seriously injured, was caused by an engine failure.
</P>
<P>
He gave no details. Other officials, who did not wish to be
identified, suggested the plane might have exploded in mid-air,
although there was no official confirmation of this.
</P>
<P>
The plane, with 77 passengers and 9 crew members aboard
crashed in the desert about 30 kilometers northeast of Sharjah, a
city some 200 kilometers west of the UAE capital Abu Dhabi at
16:45 local time (12:45GMT).
</P>
<P>
Police and rescue workers only found two survivors after the
crash and one of them, a woman passenger died Monday night on way
to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Another survivor, a crew member identified as Roberto Serje,
43, and believed to be the pilot, has been admitted to the Al
Qassim hospital in Sharjah. He was said to be in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said charred bodies were strewn across the site of
the crash in the deserts and the wreckage was spread over an area
of nearly 800 square meters.
</P>
<P>
"I have never seen a more horrible sight than this. Charred
bodies were lying all around amidst the wreckage including
aircraft seats," a rescue official who were called in to assist in
rescue operations told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I saw limbs and legs in some places. Some bodies were
intact," he said.
</P>
<P>
N. Ali, a worker from the Sharjah Oil Company, who was working
near the crash site, was among the first to reach the site.
</P>
<P>
"I saw the plane coming down at a fast speed before crashing
into a sand dune. I ran to the aircraft and saw the main part of
the aircraft burning while pieces of the jet were strewn across
the whole area," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Saef al Hajiri, Director General of the Civil
Aviation Authority in Sharjah told reporters today that all the
87 bodies of the victims have been recovered.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the plane, known as Tu-154 "disappeared from
radar screen" minutes before it was ready to land at the Sharjah
airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the plane took off from Tajik city Khodzhent, 150
kilometers south of the Tajik capital Dushanbe and it belongs to
Tajik Air Company.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the pilot apparently made no emergency
communication to Sharjah control tower before it crashed.
</P>
<P>
The captain of another passenger plane which was flying near
the Tajik plane saw the crash and reported it to the Sharjah
airport.
</P>
<P>
A Tajik delegation composed of government officials and
experts has arrived in the UAE today to probe into accident, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
