<HEADLINE> UN Chief Inspector Leaves Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief weapon inspector
Richard Butler left here today at the end of his four-day visit to
Iraq, without reaching agreement with Baghdad on access to
presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Butler had rounds of talks with Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz to persuade Iraq allowing inspectors into presidential
palaces.
</P>
<P>
He said Monday that he would come back to Baghdad on January 19
for further talks.
</P>
<P>
He will report to the U.N. Security Council on the outcome of
his visit Thursday, the first of its kind to Iraq since last
month's Iraq-U.N. standoff over the inspection.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad expelled six US inspectors with the U.N. inspection
team on November 13 on charge of espionage, triggering of a crisis
in which the U.S. threatened a war. Inspection later resumed after
Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
Butler's U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) is in charge of
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
