<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Ruling Party Adopts Tax System Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party Tuesday adopted a package of tax system reforms
for fiscal 1998 starting next April 1, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The tax system reforms, which include 750 billion yen (about
5.7 U.S. billion dollars) in national tax and 100 billion yen
(about 76.3 million dollars) in local tax, are aimed at putting
the stalled Japanese economy back on a recovery track.
</P>
<P>
Main features of the reform include reducing the basic
corporate tax rate to a postwar low of 34.5 percent from the
current 37.5 percent, abolishing the securities trading tax in two
stages by the end of 1999, and drastically easing land-related
taxes.
</P>
<P>
The tax cuts are expected to result in an average real
corporate tax cut of 200 billion yen (about 1.5 billion dollars)
annually for fiscal years 1998 through 2003.
</P>
<P>
The proposal forces the government of Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto to back away from plans to reduce the issuance of
deficit-covering bonds by 1.25 trillion yen (about 9.5 billion
dollars) annually to cut the country's fiscal deficit to three
percent or less of gross domestic product by fiscal 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
