<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM: EU Membership Decision a Disappointment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said today that the European Union's decision to reject
his nation as a candidate for EU membership is a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
During an early morning press briefing just prior to the
scheduled North Atlantic Council at foreign ministerial level, Cem
said: "The summit decision, on certain point, was unfair,
sometimes biased and sometimes with the connotation of double
standards. Sometimes it was based on exaggerated allegations."
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) at its last weekend summit in Luxembourg
decided to invite Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks early next year.
</P>
<P>
Five other nations -- Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and
Slovakia -- were put on a slower negotiating track by the
15-nation union, leaving Turkey, a 34-year applicant, completely
in the cold.
</P>
<P>
The result of the summit was disappointing for Turkey, but "It
was not an obsession for Turkey and we will not treat it as an
event that will have an impact on the course of Turkey," said the
foreign minister, adding that his nation did expect to have a
better place within the EU.
</P>
<P>
Furious over the rejection as a candidate for EU membership,
Turkey refused to continue its political dialogue with the union
by turning away an offer from EU on Sunday to take part in a
pan-European conference which the EU heads of state and government
expected to serve as a means of keeping Turkey within its
enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said the pan-European
conference, slated for next March, had lost its meaning for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
But the Turkish foreign minister said at the press briefing:
"The European Union is a goal for Turkey and we will try our best
to attain that goal."
</P>
<P>
Observers here were afraid that the EU decision would sour the
relations between Turkey and other NATO member states, especially
Greece, on their disputes over the east Aegean Sea and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Turkey reached an agreement with Greece on
the military flight issue over the east Aegean Sea area which
finally moved one of the remaining obstacles for the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization to agree on its internal adaptation
for a new, streamlined command structure.
</P>
<P>
The Turkey-Greece regional dispute was started in 1957 and was
aggravated by their dispute over the island state of Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
