<HEADLINE> Chinese Commission Asks Cities To Develop New Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's State Science and
Technology Commission today said that cities should make the
development of new industries one of their major economic
development programs.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, the vice-minister in charge of the SSTC, speaking
at the Great Hall of the People today, said that new industries,
especially high-tech industry, can change patterns of economic
growth and stimulate it.
</P>
<P>
Xu spoke at a meeting on the city of Zhuzhou's new industrial
development strategy, sponsored by SSTC, and said the strategy was
drawn up by government departments, experts and economists with
research on technology, the economy, and marketing, and will be
easy to adopt by a city's policy makers and administrative
departments.
</P>
<P>
He called on other cities to learn from Zhuzhou in making
industrial development plans for the next century to avoid blindly
introducing foreign investment, technology or equipment.
</P>
<P>
Zhuzhou, in Hunan Province, which has 3.7 million people, was
one of China's first group of new industrial cities after it was
founded in 1949, and China's first aircraft and electric
locomotives were produced there.
</P>
<P>
The city's high-tech products output is expected to be worth 3
billion yuan (360 million US dollars) this year and the city was
listed as one of the pioneer cities in improving its economy with
the help science and technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
