<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECD) said in a perspective report published on Monday that the
"financial turbulences" which are shaking Southeast Asia have a
double effect, causing less economic growth and less
inflation. The growth of European Union countries risks to be
amputed by 0.3 percent in 1997 and 0.8 percent in 1998 because of
the Asia financial crisis. Meanwhile, inflation will be reduced by
0.3 percent in EU countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
-- The international terrorist Carlos, who has been appearing
since last Friday before the Assize Court of Paris for the murder
of three people in 1975 in rue Toullier in Paris, continued his
strategy of provocations by presenting himself as "international
revolutionary." The defense lawyer of Carlos decided on Monday
to withdraw from the process with the pretext that the court did
not give her the means to ensure the defense of his client.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde:
</P>
<P>
-- French experts in charge of treating drug addicts have urged
a revision of the law of December 31, 1970, which makes all drug
addicts law-breakers by imposing prison sentences and fines for
the simple use of drug whatever its nature is. They made the
appeal after attending the first national meeting on drug abuse
and addiction on December 12-13 at the State Secretariat of
Health. In 1996, some 12,000 people were condemned in the name of
the repressive anti-drug law in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
