<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesian Rupiah Drops to new Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah fell by
almost 16 percent Monday to a record low of 5,800 against the U.S.
dollar, and closed at 5,600 to 5,900 with thin volume.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the Indonesian currency has been the hardest
hit by the regional financial crisis which broke out following the
Thai baht's devaluation in July this year, dealers here said.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped by more than 100 percent
against the U.S. dollar since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Economists and analysts have attributed the drastic fall of the
rupiah to, among other things, weak regional currencies and
lingering unfounded rumors about the health of President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The currencies of the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia and
Singapore as well as South Korea have all dropped in recent days
to record lows against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here believed that the main reason for the
weakness of the rupiah is fears over President Soeharto's health.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the rupiah plummeted by almost 15 percent to a new
low, crashing below 5,000 to the dollar after the government
announced that Soeharto canceled plans to attend the ASEAN
informal summit in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on the advice of his
doctors.
</P>
<P>
The announcement sent a chill through the country's financial
markets. The main price index on the Jakarta Stock Exchange closed
at a four-year low at 339.53 points Monday, down 118 percent from
its highest level of 740.93 points on July 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said the president's health
had been restored, but his doctors advised him against travelling.
The president had also canceled a planned visit to the grave of
his wife, Mme. Tien Soeharto, in Solo, Central Java, over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
"If he takes a long journey, his health will diminish and it
will take time to restore it again," Moerdiono explained.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was ordered by doctors to take a full 10-day rest
after a four-nation tour last month.
</P>
<P>
The president, 76, attended the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) leaders' informal meeting in Vancouver, Canada,
and visited Namibia, South Africa and Saudi Arabia, from November
18 to 29.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economists and analysts here said that the rupiah
exchange rate against the greenback will improve if the government
implements economic reforms and deregulation measures consistently
and not partially or half-heartedly.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Anwar Nasution, an economics professor with
the University of Indonesia, observers have the impression that
the government is half-hearted about implementing economic reforms
or doing so only partially. This causes doubts from businessmen
and traders, he said.
</P>
<P>
In mid-October, the Indonesian government asked the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank for help and received a 23 billion U.S. dollars
bailout financial package. Other bilateral agreements were also
made available to supplement the financial package.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken several financial reform measures
since November, including the closure of 16 private banks in the
country.
</P>
<P>
World Bank country director for Indonesia Dennis De Tray on
Monday also urged the Indonesian government and the private sector
to provide credible information to help restore public confidence
in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar on Indonesia's macro-economy. De Tray
said the government needed to show a strong and quick sign of its
implementation of reform measures to cope with the currency
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"The government has to deal with the crisis in a highly
efficient way by using models of global rules," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia's monetary crisis, unlike Thailand's, was
largely driven by domestic factors rather than by overseas
factors.
</P>
<P>
He believed Indonesia would be able to come out of the monetary
crisis if it stuck to the short- and long-term measures in dealing
with the monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the Center for Strategic and
International Studies (CSIS) Mari E. Pangestu shared De Tray's
view, saying that the monetary crisis stemmed from the lack of
confidence in the market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Umar Juoro, an economist at the Institute for
National Development Studies (INDES), linked the latest drop in
the rupiah exchange rate to the fact that the public at large has
no idea what actions the government plans to take in the wake of
the IMF deal.
</P>
<P>
"If the government is committed to economic recovery under the
IMF scheme, it should make clear quickly what areas will be
subject to economic reform, the budget or infrastructure for
example, and explain publicly what further steps are to be taken,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
