<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Slams Idea of ANC-IFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
opposition parties have slammed the idea of a merger between the
African National Congress (ANC) and the Inkatha Freedom Party
(IFP), warning that such a move could lead to a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
The warning followed South African President Nelson Mandela's
remarks on Sunday that the fusion of the two parties would be a
crucial first step in bringing about unity in South Africa, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he would be very happy if Buthelezi were made
deputy president of the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Mandela appealed to the Pan Africanist
Congress, Azanian People's Organization (Azapo) and the IFP to
join the ANC.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders expressed their concerns in separate
comments about a possible merger of the two major black parties.
</P>
<P>
National Party leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk said: "It is
very important to have a strong black party, like the IFP,
staying outside of the ANC's sphere of influence."
</P>
<P>
He believed that Buthelezi would not be lured by the proposal.
</P>
<P>
"I would be very surprised if the IFP accepts the ANC
proposal," van Schalkwyk said.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon described such attempts as
dangerous to South Africa's budding democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Simply trying to give the ANC a monopoly of political power,
either by default or by design, is inherently unhealthy and a
very dangerous idea."
</P>
<P>
The ANC already had far too much power, both in the public
service and the political realm, Leon said.
</P>
<P>
The Freedom Front, the PAC, the Azapo, and the United
Democratic Movement also voiced their opposition to a possible
merger.
</P>
<P>
The IFP said Monday that it had not been approached officially
by the ANC on the matter.
</P>
<P>
It said it was not considering such a move because it was busy
preparing for the 1999 general election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
