<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parliament Mulls Delay of Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Special Committee of
the National Assembly of Cambodia proposed Tuesday to postpone
the national general elections scheduled for May 23, 1998, by half
a year.
</P>
<P>
At an assembly meeting, Second Deputy Prime Minister and
Co-minister of the Interior Affairs Sar Kheng suggested that the
elections be postponed to July 31 or October 18 because of the
shortage of time for preparation.
</P>
<P>
After discussions, the Special Committee of the assembly
suggested November 22 as the date and asked for a voting on it
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Cambodian constitution, general elections are held
every five years, and the latest one was done on May 23, 1993,
under the U.N. supervision. 
