<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 85 Killed in Tajik Aircraft Crash in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Eighty five people were
killed and one was seriously injured when a Tajik civil plane
crashed in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) Monday afternoon,
latest reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The plane, with 77 passengers and nine crew members on board
crashed in the desert 32 kilometers northeast of Sharjah, a UAE
city some 200 kilometers west of the UAE capital of Abu Dhabi
at 16:45 local time (12:45 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Police and rescue workers only found two survivors after the
crash and one of them, a women passenger died on the way to
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Another survivor, a crew member identified as Roberto Serje
and believed to be the pilot, has been admitted to the Al
Qassim hospital in Sharjah in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Saef al Hajiri, Director General of the Civil
Aviation Authority in Sharjah told reporters that police and
rescue workers have found 55 bodies of the victims and they are
trying to search more.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said charred bodies were strewn across the site of
the crash in the deserts and the wreckage of the aircraft was
spread over an area of nearly 800 square meters.
</P>
<P>
"I have never seen a more horrible sight than this.
Charred bodies were lying all around amidst the wreckage
including aircraft seats," a rescue official who was called in
to assist in rescue operations told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I saw limbs and legs in some places. Some bodies were
intact," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the plane, known as Tupolev 154 "disappeared
from radascreen" minites before it was ready to land at the
Sharjah airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the plane took off from Tajik city Khodzhent, 150
kilometers south of the Tajik capital of Dushanve. All victims are
Tajik citizens, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the pilot apparently made no emergency
communication with Sharjah control tower before it crashed.
</P>
<P>
"When we suddenly lost radio contact, we realized that
something was wrong with the plane. The crash must have taken
place a couple of minutes later," Sheikh Abdullah bin Mohammed
al Thani, President of the Civil Aviation Authority in Sharjah
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The captain of another passenger plane which was flying
near the Tajik plane saw the crash and reported it to the
Sharjah airport.
</P>
<P>
Investigators have found the digital flight data recorder,
commonly known as the black box and the cockpit voice
recorder.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed al Thani said his authority will hold a press
conference today to "explain all aspects of the accident."
</P>
<P>
A Tajik governmental delegation will arrive in the UAE today
to investigate all details of the accident, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Tu-154 Tajik airliner's crash is the second recorded
air disaster in the UAE involving passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
On September 23, 1983, an Abu Dhabi-bound Gulf Air Boeing
737 coming from Karachi crashed in the desert, killing 112
passengers and crew members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
