<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM, Iraq Fail to Agree on Access to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief arms inspector
Richard Bulter announced last night that Iraq has made its stance
clear that it would never allow U.N. weapon monitoring team to
enter its presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Bulter, Executive Chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, made the remarks at a news conference held here
late Monday here.
</P>
<P>
"Iraqi side insisted that we would never be able to inspect
presidential sites," said Butler, stressing that the Iraqi
decision "did constitute the derogation from the (Security)
Council's insistence that UNSCOM should be able to go anywhere,
at any time."
</P>
<P>
Butler said Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, the top
negotiator on Iraqi side, told him "make it clear to the Council
that we would defend that in front of the Council."
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM chairman, who arrived in Baghdad last Friday and
held three rounds of talks with Iraqi officials, said he would
leave here Tuesday and report to the Security Council the results
of their talks this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We had a long discussion about what would constitute a
presidential site, I was given no clear answer," said Butler,
adding that his requirement that Iraq provide UNSCOM with a list
or map of the presidential sites had been turned down by the
Iraqi side, which argued that "might help those who wish to bomb
Iraq do so more precisely."
</P>
<P>
The chairman also said that the report given by Aziz
during Sunday evening's technical talks on Iraq's biological
program was "nothing new."
</P>
<P>
However, when being asked whether his talks with Iraqi side
could be characterized as a failure, Butler said he wouldn't
readily use the word.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been some progress in technical issues
disarmament during their technical talks in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
"I have agreed in principle that we can in the future
subject the difference of opinions to technical examination
meetings," he said.
</P>
<P>
With respect to access, the two sides also made some progress
by clarity of definition, said Butler, explaining that the great
bulk of Iraq would be open, and he obtained an agreement from Iraq
that access to those sensitive sites declared by Iraq would be on
better bases than in the past.
</P>
<P>
"We'll have more people, a short period of time before we
are let in, their two are very important considerations," said
Butler.
</P>
<P>
On the question of "Iraq's unilateral decision" to say that
presidential sites will be off limits forever, Butler said
that is something he cannot deal with, and that he would
refer it to the Council for its view and judgement.
</P>
<P>
Butler said he agreed to come back to Baghdad on January
19, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
