<HEADLINE> Egypt: No Dialog With Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has ruled out any dialog with terrorist groups, saying "there is
no question about that."
</P>
<P>
"The state won't enter into dialog with the groups of killers
who have violated religion and the law," he told the religious
weekly Akidati on its sixth year of publication on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"All other claims in circulation to the contrary are completely
baseless," Mubarak stressed, whose remarks were carried on today's
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government has rejected several ceasefire
proposals by jailed militant leaders earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
But reports have sprouted up recently about secret mediation
through a journalist between the government and militant groups
after Usama Rushdie, a leader of Egypt's largest Islamic militant
group Gamaa Islamiya offered an olive branch to Cairo and proposed
the opening of negotiations last month.
</P>
<P>
The Gamaa Islamiya leadership condemned the massacre in Luxor
less than two weeks after the organization claimed responsibility
for Egypt's bloodiest terrorist attack since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The brutal slaying of 62 people in the southern tourist city of
Luxor on November 17 was carried out by six Gamaa members without
getting instructions from the leadership, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The president reaffirmed that perpetrators of brutal attacks
were not Muslims and regretted the "exaggeration by some foreign
media" in linking terrorism to Islam.
</P>
<P>
He added that fighting terrorism was the task of the whole
society.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also assured the security of Egypt and the ability of
Egyptian security agencies to crack down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"To have some security personnel neglecting their duty does not
encompass the whole apparatus," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lax security has been widely blamed for the fatal incident as
Mubarak called the arrangement there "a joke."  
</P>
</TEXT>
