<HEADLINE> Israel's Unemployment Rises Continually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The number of jobseekers in
Israel rose 1.2 percent in November to a total of 151,600,
compared to 149,800 in October, today's The Jerusalem Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli Employment Service as saying that
there was also a 0.1 percent increase in the number of new
immigrant jobseekers last month to 11,000.
</P>
<P>
Since July this year, Israel's unemployment has risen
continually. And the third-quarter unemployment rate had jumped to
8.1 percent, the highest in three-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Finance Minister Ya'akov Neeman has declared
unemployment as the number one problem facing the Israeli economy.
</P>
<P>
A group of ministers, including Neeman and Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky, is currently preparing documentation on
unemployment for consideration by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Israel's Trade Union leader Amir Peretz said he
will lead an unwavering battle against jobs being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to establish an emergency fund
with 1 percent of the budget, or 1 billion shekels (about
290 million U.S. dollars), that would be earmarked to fight
unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
