<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso plunged
further to a record low of 40.214 pesos against the U.S. dollar in
today's trading on the Philippine Dealing System (PDS).
</P>
<P>
The peso was averaged at 39.910 to the greenback in morning
trading on the PDS, the electronic currency exchange, down 1.563
pesos from Monday's reference rate of 38.347 pesos.
</P>
<P>
The trading was suspended according to a system of volatility
bands which limits daily fluctuations in the peso-dollar rate to
no more than 4 percent from the previous day's average level.
</P>
<P>
The peso struck all three volatility caps today with a thin
transaction volume of 7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the consecutive falls of the peso to a
plunge in the Thai baht which they expected will push the peso
down further in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Executive Secretary Ruben Torres said in an
interview today that the peso depreciation was just a temporary
aberrations triggered by the heavy importation and big demand for
foreign currencies during the Christmas season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
