<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Minister on China's Foreign Trade and World Trade in 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade still
has momentum this year following last year's relatively low
growth, said Wu Yi, Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the People's Daily, the country's leading
newspaper, Wu said that trade in the first 11 months of this year
was worth 286.8 billion US dollars, an increase of 14 percent over
the same period of last year, and she described four
characteristics of this year's trade:
</P>
<P>
-- Steady development with relatively rapid growth. Trade this
year was up 11.7 percent in the first quarter, 14.3 percent in the
second, and 14.9 percent in the third, from last year's
figures. The increase for the fourth quarter is expected to be
about 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Greater recovery from the relatively low growth last
year. Trade in the first half of this year was up 13.1 percent and
13.8 percent from the same periods in 1996 and 1995, respectively.
</P>
<P>
-- Conflicts in the foreign trade mix have declined remarkably,
as seen in the rapid increase in exports by China's state-owned
enterprises, import increases, an improvement in the foreign trade
products mix, and more diversity.
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign trade has played an increasingly important role in
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Use of overseas investment continued to grow this year, Wu
said, and China had used 35.598 billion US dollars of investment
in the first 10 months, an increase of 8.27 percent over the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October, China had approved a combined total of
more than 300,000 overseas-funded enterprises with a total of 510
billion US dollars in investment, over 210 billion of which is
being used, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there has been progress in economic and
technological co-operation with other countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, China's average tariff rate has fallen 60.6
percent, from 43.2 percent to 17 percent, she said, and President
Jiang Zemin committed himself to a further lowering to 10 percent
by the year 2005 during APEC's fifth informal meeting not long ago.
</P>
<P>
She said she believes this will prove attractive for overseas
investment, bring advanced technology and equipment for
state-owned enterprises, increase Chinese competitiveness in the
international market, and create favorable conditions for overseas
products to enter China's market, thereby increasing imports and
reducing China's foreign trade surplus.
</P>
<P>
For next year, she said that there are both challenges and
opportunities. The former are the negative impact on the world's
economy from the financial turmoil caused by the financial crisis
in Southeast Asia, the similarity of export products of China and
Southeast Asian nations, the increasing trade protectionism
against China, and trade conflicts caused by China's foreign trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that in 1998, China will continue to increase exports
and improve the trade products mix and market orientation, and
work for a trade balance.
</P>
<P>
She estimates that China's foreign trade next year will
continue to increase by a higher rate than China's national
economy, and China will attract more overseas investment and
provide preferential policies for high-tech products,
overseas-funded projects, and imported technology and equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Minister on China's Foreign Trade and World Trade in 1997 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The global multi-lateral trade system and regional economic
groups are growing and their effect on world trade has drawn
people's greater attention.
</P>
<P>
Regional economic groups like the European Union (EU) and the
North America Free Trade Area (NAFTA) have adopted totally to the
open market and free trade among their members, she pointed
out. This allows for the free flow of goods, services, capital,
and labor, she said, and is good for the effective allocation of
resources and economic growth in these regions.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, the top priority of these regional economic
groups is to have relatively favorable policies and various levels
of free trade inside the regions. They maintain the original
tariff or non-tariff policies outside the region, giving rise to
discriminatory trade barriers and investment practice.
</P>
<P>
"If this goes on for a long time, discriminatory trade barriers
and investment practices will inevitably affect the economic
development of other countries and regions with increasing
international trade conflicts and by eroding multi-lateral trade
systems," she said.
</P>
<P>
As long as these regional trade groups stick to an "open
regionalism" and have non-discriminatory principles, they will not
give rise to new trade and investment obstacles, and existing
trade and investment barriers will gradually be lowered or even
eliminated in the process of liberalization and will facilitate
trade and investment, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region has become the most vigorous region for
China's economic growth. China's trade with the region accounts
for 80 percent of the country's total foreign trade and 90
percent of its overseas investment is from the region, she added.
</P>
<P>
China has always actively supported and participated in Asia
Pacific Economic Co-operation (APEC), she said, and that one of
APEC's main items this year, the liberalization of certain trade
sectors, will promote liberalization of trade and investment in
APEC.
</P>
<P>
She said that China will participate in discussions about the
liberalization of trade sectors, while taking the progress of its
own reforms and opening up and economic growth into
consideration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Minister on China's Foreign Trade and World Trade in 1997 (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There has been progress in talks on China's WTO membership this
year, both in bilateral talks and multilateral panels, and China
has negotiated bilateral market access since August, she said.
</P>
<P>
More than ten countries, including New Zealand, the Republic of
Korea and Hungary, have talked with China about goods trade and
service trade and nine have signed agreements with China.
</P>
<P>
Trade talks about goods trade between China and Japan are
finished, and service trade talks are underway, and talks between
China and Europe have reached the final stage.
</P>
<P>
During the Sino-US summit in Washington this October, the US
side reiterated in the Sino-US Joint Statement that it would speed
up talks with China on China's entry into the WTO at an early
date. The Chinese delegation also discussed this in detail in
Geneva this month.
</P>
<P>
The WTO working group on China has held three meetings this
year, but market access is still a difficult point, and the
Chinese have said that they are ready to take action with a
flexible attitude toward the demands of WTO members in bilateral
talks.
</P>
<P>
If the major WTO members have an active, flexible and pragmatic
attitude toward problems with China's WTO membership, instead of
making exorbitant demands, talks will make progress.
</P>
<P>
There is an imbalance in trade with the US, but in recent
years, China has taken steps to try to balance that trade by
encouraging Chinese enterprises to import from the US, and China
has sent several trade missions and bought nearly 10 billion US
dollars worth of goods.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese market is more open and trade partners will all be
treated equally. China is willing to see the US expand its exports
to China, and hopes the US side can reduce its controls on exports
to China and take steps to encourage US enterprises to export to
China.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been a conduit for foreign funds into China and
for foreign trade, and after its return, this role has not and
will not change.
</P>
<P>
According to China's customs, from April to June of this year,
trade between inland areas and Hong Kong was worth about 13
billion US dollars, and after the return, trade from July to
September was similar and amounted to 12.8 billion US dollars
worth. Hong Kong is still the inland areas' biggest export market
and second biggest trade partner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Supports Ties Between EU, Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said here Monday that Italy supports Yugoslavia in
its efforts to normalize relations with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters following talks with his Yugoslav
counterpart Milan Milutinovich, Dini said Italy intends to raise
the issue, with the European Commission, about certain stagnation
in the relations between the two sides .
</P>
<P>
Dini believed that a "real channel" can be found to bridge
differences between the EU and Yugoslavia, and to resolve all
their bilateral problems, especially those concerning their
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also discussed the protection of
investment in Yugoslavia, the avoidance of double taxation,
bilateral cooperation in technology and highway and air
transportation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevich also met with Dini. The
two expressed satisfaction in the smooth development on bilateral
relations and stressed that states of the former Yugoslavia
should strengthen their economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
