</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- About 123,000 children aged 14-17 work in
America's fields, according to an unreleased Labor Department
survey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 13,100 children worked illegally last year
in garment industry sweatshops -- factories that repeatedly
violate federal wages and hours laws, according to study
commissioned by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Many of the children working in America are frequently
underpaid, often unaccompanied and largely unprotected -- a shadow
generation made prematurely adult, moving from coast to coast,
border to border. (US-Child Labor)
</P>
