<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ANC Conference Eyes 1999 Election and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The 50th national
conference of South Africa's ruling African National Congress
(ANC) will discuss crucial policies and prepare for the 1999
general election to lead the country into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be held from today to Saturday in
Mafikeng, capital of South Africa's North-West Province.
</P>
<P>
At the five-day gathering, ANC Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
will step into President Nelson Mandela's shoes as ANC leader and
in 1999 become president of the country. He is left unchallenged
for the top ANC job.
</P>
<P>
ANC national chairman and the party's provincial leader of
Kwazulu-Natal, Jacob Zuma, won the support of the country's all
nine provincial structures of the ANC to take the post of deputy
president.
</P>
<P>
Mandela on Sunday heaped praises on his successors.
</P>
<P>
"He (Mbeki) is a man of exceptional gifts, very respectful,
very warm, very sensitive to the suffering of our people."
</P>
<P>
He referred to Zuma as an "outstanding leader, generous, full
of self respect and highly talented."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who has already been left to run the day-to-day affairs
of the government and preside over cabinet meetings, is now
actually the de facto president of the country.
</P>
<P>
Besides the election of a new leadership after Mandela's
retirement, the conference is also expected to prepare the ANC
for the 1999 general election without Mandela, which is believed
to be harder than the first all-race election in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that the ANC is losing members because its
failure to fulfill some of its promises before the 1994 election.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also give the ANC an opportunity to
reflect on its past three and a half years in office. But party
leaders have repeatedly said that there would not be big changes
in its policy.
</P>
<P>
The country's macro-economic policy is expected to be a hot
issue at the conference as the country is still facing the same
problems during the apartheid years: unemployment and social
disorder.
</P>
<P>
With a new election only 18 months away, the ANC has so far
failed to deliver on its promises of houses, jobs and better life
for the black majority.
</P>
<P>
The government's Growth, Employment and Redistribution (Gear)
macro-economic program started in 1996 also failed to reach its
target. According to the ambitious plan, the economy should grow
at an annual rate of about six percent, but the actual
achievement this year was only about two percent. Instead of job
creation, the country is losing jobs, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
Another hot issue at the conference might be the role in the
ANC of the party's most controversial figure, Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Madikizela-Mandela, president of ANC Women's League and member
of the all-powerful ANC National Executive Committee, also eyed
the post of deputy presidency.
</P>
<P>
The former wife of President Mandela was excluded from a list
of nominations for the top six jobs of the ANC revealed last
week, but she still has a chance through nominations directly
from the floor.
</P>
<P>
Her ambition may be further curtailed as the party has
announced that the percentage of approval required for floor
nominations could be increased to 25 or even 30 percent from the
present 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Her reputation suffered a damaging blow after a nine-day
hearing of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission implicated her
in more than a dozen cases of murder, abduction and torture
during the apartheid era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
