<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Army Team Visits Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A team of 25 Kenyan army
officers is visiting Uganda for talks on regional cooperation,
Ugandan officials said.
</P>
<P>
Rebecca Kadaga, the state minister for foreign affairs, said
here Monday that Kenyan army officers came to Uganda to "find
ways of cooperation in the army in training and exchange of
information between security forces".
</P>
<P>
Mugisha Muntu, Ugandan army commander, said the East African
Cooperation mandates exchange of information among east African
armies.
</P>
<P>
The general said this is the first visit of its kind from the
Kenyan army.
</P>
<P>
An official in the Kenyan High Commission in Kampala told
local paper "The Crusader" that the team of Kenyan officers
headed by Lt. General Opande would discuss the possibility of an
east African army.
</P>
<P>
But Kadaga denied the version, saying, "we don't intend to
form the east African army".
</P>
<P>
Majority of the 25 officers are from the National College of
Defense of Kenya and others from the navy, air forces and police
of Kenya, Kadaga told the paper. The team has already visited
Tanzania and Ethiopia under an agreement of the East African
Cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
