<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, ASEAN to Work Together on Regional Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and leaders of the member states of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations issued a joint statement following their
meeting here Tuesday, vowing to work together for maintaining
regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pledged to "resolve their differences or disputes
through peaceful means, without resorting to the threat or use of
force," as they had recognized that "the maintenance of regional
peace and stability served the interests of all parties."
</P>
<P>
"The parties concerned agree to resolve their disputes in the
South China Sea through friendly consultations and negotiations in
accordance with universally recognized international law," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed "to continue to exercise self-restraint and handle
relevant differences in a cool and constructive manner," which was
"in the interest of promoting peace and stability as well as
enhancing mutual confidence in the region."
</P>
<P>
China reaffirmed that it would respect and support the efforts
of ASEAN to establish a Zone of Peace, Freedom and Neutrality in
Southeast Asia, the statement said. "In this connection, China
welcomed the entry into force of the Southeast Asia Nuclear
Weapons-Free Zone Treaty."
</P>
<P>
Leaders of ASEAN member states expressed their belief that a
stable, peaceful and prosperous China would constitute an
important factor for the long term peace, stability and
development of the Asia-Pacific region in particular and of the
world in general.
</P>
<P>
The also reaffirmed their continued adherence to the "one
China" policy.
</P>
<P>
"China appreciated and supported ASEAN's positive role in
international and regional affairs," while "ASEAN member states
believed that a stable, peaceful and prosperous China would
constitute an important factor for the long-term peace, stability
and development of the Asia-Pacific region in particular and of
the world in general."
</P>
<P>
The two sides pledged to make joint efforts to respond
positively to the challenges of a dynamic regional and
international environment, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
