<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000 Girl Dropouts Back to School in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 girl dropouts
in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have gone
back to school under a special aid program, a local official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The region now has about 60,000 school dropouts, 70 percent of
them being girls, according to statistics from its education
commission.
</P>
<P>
From 1994, Xinjiang started to carry out the "Spring Bud"
program, a nationwide education project for aiding girl dropouts,
especially in poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Some 16 "Spring Bud" classes have been established in Xinjiang,
with an investment of 1.56 million yuan (about 188,000 US dollars)
from governmental departments.
</P>
<P>
The girl students in the classes also receive labor skill
training while taking general knowledge courses. 
</P>
