<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Size of Shanghai's Restaurants Becoming Larger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Many restaurants in Shanghai,
China's industrial and commercial city, are building their
reputation with large size.
</P>
<P>
Most large restaurants opened in the city this year are
successful. A typical example is the Hongziji Restaurant,
Shanghai's largest restaurant serving Chinese food which can seat
up to 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Large catering places are drawing customers from small ones
nearby. And, of the 25,000 restaurants in Shanghai, less than 800
have over 500 seats.
</P>
<P>
Many restaurants are trying to strengthen their position
by adopting new service items and creating appealing dining
environment in a bid to narrow the gap between themselves and the
international style.
</P>
<P>
Offering dainty local food or special cuisines from other
places of the country without losing their distinctive
characteristics is deemed by many Shanghai restaurants as a way to
survive in the ever intensifying market competition.
</P>
<P>
These trends are predicted to go on well into early next
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
