<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Highway to Relieve Grotto From Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A cluster of 1,500-year old
grottos with numerous Buddhist statures in north China will be
protected from the threat of erosion by heavy coal dust.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a highway has recently unveiled near Datong
in Shanxi Province as a main line of transportation to replace the
current one that goes in close parallel to Yungang, China's
largest grotto which dates back to mid fifth century and has some
51,000 Buddhist statures in 45 caves, with the biggest one
measuring 17 meters tall.
</P>
<P>
The grotto and Buddhist statures have been invaded by emission
and coated with dust left over by thousands of heavy trucks
running day and night on the highway to take coal out of the
province, known for its rich coal resources and production.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial construction officials, the new
26-kilometer long highway has gained an government investment of
some 256 million yuan and will be completed in one year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
