<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Big Powers Readjust Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 has been a busy
year witnessing very active diplomacy by the world big
powers. Leaders of China, the United States, Russia and Japan as
well as those from Western Europe have engaged in frequent
bilateral or multilateral contacts. This is a situation rarely
seen in world history of diplomacy and reflects the fact that
relations among big powers are undergoing a profound and
significant readjustment.
</P>
<P>
One salient feature in this readjustment is that, proceeding
from their own strategic interests, the big powers attached
importance to the common interests, but did not give up their self
interests. They admitted the existence of contradictions or
disputes among them, but spared no efforts on building strategic
partnership towards the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The China-U.S. relationship enjoyed an improvement after
suffering a period of ups and downs. Chinese President Jiang Zemin
visited the United States from October 26 to November 3. In the
China-U.S. Joint Statement, signed during the visit, the two
countries announced their commitment to the establishment of a
constructive strategic partnership oriented toward the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Through joint efforts, they also concluded a package of trade
and economic cooperation agreements and initiated actions on the
program of peaceful use of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese-Russian relations were also further
expanded. Jiang's visit to Russia in April and Boris Yeltsin's
November visit to China added new contents to their existing
21st-century-oriented strategic relationship of equality and
trust: the signing of a joint statement on world polarization and
the establishment of a new international order, and the singing of
an agreement on the reduction of military forces in their border
areas. These documents provided the world with new modes of proper
handling of relations among nations and of building regional
security and stability systems, modes worthy of promotion and
different from the Cold War thinking.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Russia, China and Japan as well as China and France
all have worked hard this year in pairs for partnerships geared to
the next century. During his visit to Russia in early November,
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and Yeltsin approved a
plan on bilateral cooperation in politics, economy and finance,
and also agreed to make efforts to conclude a peace treaty before
the year 2000 and move towards a "real partnership."
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Chinese Premier Li Peng visited Japan and,
together with Japanese leaders, re-affirmed their commitment to a
21st-century-oriented good-neighborly cooperative friendship
between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Before Li's Japan visit, French President Jacques Chirac
arrived in China in May. During his stay, Chirac and Jiang
promised to establish a long-term comprehensive partnership
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States decided to establish a strategic
partnership as early as in 1994, but contradictions between them
were deepened because of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's
eastward expansion, the center issue of many meetings among
leaders of Russia, the United States and west European
countries. Although they have reached a sort of compromise over
the issue, contradictions remain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oldest Oilfield Stabilizing Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Yumen
Oilfield, the country's oldest, has stabilized its annual crude
oil output at 400,000 tons since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Oil exploration experts of the oilfield in Gansu Province said
that the output can be kept through the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yumen Oilfield, known as the cradle of China's oil industry, is
responsible for petroleum exploration and development in a
500,000-sq-km area that covers west of Helan Mountains, east of
Dunhuang City, south of Sino-Mongolian border and north of Qilian
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
It was first discovered in 1939 and exploration was also
carried out the same year. Five small oilfields have been built in
Yumen Oilfield where petroleum reserves have been verified at
90.06 million tons, with recoverable reserves estimated at 32.46
million tons.
</P>
<P>
As New China's first oil production base, the Yumen Oilfield
has so far pumped a total of 26.64 million tons of crude oil. It
has reported decreases in oil output ever since it produced its
record output of 1.4 million tons in 1959.
</P>
<P>
To curb the decrease, engineers have been busy doing more
research on late-period development at Yumen Oilfield, while
applying ten new exploration techniques.
</P>
<P>
Scientific progress has helped increase Yumen Oilfield's annual
oil output by 26,000 tons at present, up from 19,000 tons in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Big Powers Readjust Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Readjustment of relations among big powers this year manifests
the following characteristics.
</P>
<P>
-- It is based on the common interests of different levels,
instead of military cooperation. The common interests are of
global, regional and bilateral nature in the fields of politics,
security, trade, economy, energy, environmental protection,
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Of them, the economic interest is playing an increasingly more
important role in the big-power relations. Trade volume between
China and the United States, and that between China and Japan, in
1996, reached as high as 42.8 billion and 60 billion U.S. dollars
respectively. Mutual complementary and great potentiality have
become one of the most powerful motive forces for the improvement
and development of China-U.S. and China-Japan relations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to join efforts on the exploration of natural
resources in Siberia, Russia, has laid a foundation for
reconciliation of relationship between Japan and Russia, while
China and Russia have agreed to strive to bring their bilateral
trade volume up to 20 billion dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
-- It advocates settlement of existing differences and disputes
through the means of dialogue rather than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
No pair of big powers can be free from disputes even when they
enjoy a strategic partnership. It is, however, important for them
to follow the two principles when dealing with their dispute.
</P>
<P>
One is the principle of dialogue or consultation on the basis
of equality and mutual respect, and the other the principle of
seeking common ground while reserving differences. If the
differences cannot be removed for the time being, just shelf them
and never let individual cases affect the overall situation.
</P>
<P>
To make sure the observance of the principles, some big
countries have already established mechanism for regular meetings
between their leaders.
</P>
<P>
-- It does not pose any "threat" to a third party.
</P>
<P>
Opinion in some of the Western countries that strategic
partnership between big powers represents a kind of alliance
against a third country is utterly groundless. Both China and the
United States made it clear that their aim to build a constructive
strategic partnership is to promote world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese-Russian strategic friendship of cooperation is
characterized by "non-alignment, non-confrontation and targeting
at no third parties," and is designed to help maintain a balance
of power and establish a stable, just international political and
economic order of peace.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the China-France long-term comprehensive partnership
is aimed at bringing about a more prosperous, stable, secure and
balanced world.
</P>
<P>
-- It does not prevent any country from developing relations
with a third party, rather it helps improve ties among big powers.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's U.S. visit has not only played a positive role in the
improvement of China-U.S. relations, but also started a chain
reaction on relations of other pairs of big powers.
</P>
<P>
Following Jiang's nine-day U.S. tour, Hashimoto visited Russia,
Yeltsin visited China and then Li Peng visited Japan. All these on
the whole pushed forward the development of Japan-Russia,
China-Russia and China-Japan relations, as well as helped improve
the less-than-satisfying Japan-Russia relations in particular.
</P>
<P>
Partnership emerges among big powers not by accident, but is a
phase manifestation of readjustment of big power relations in the
post-Cold War world polarization process.
</P>
<P>
After the collapse of the bi-polar pattern, the world is
becoming multi-polar instead of single-polar. Every big country is
struggling to strengthen its comprehensive national power so as to
jockey for position in the future pattern of a multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of strategic partnership among big powers
since the beginning of 1997, whatever their subjective aims, is in
fact a confirmation of the trend of world polarization and is
beneficial to world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
However, going against this trend, the United States has never
given up its scheme of a U.S.-dominated single-polar world, busy
strengthening strategic cooperation of military alliance by
promoting NATO expansion in the West and U.S.-Japan defense
cooperation in the East. Such U.S. insistence on Cold-War thinking
has brought in complicating factors into the current big-power
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- "Economic democracy" is the
main stream in most families in Shanghai, the leading metropolis
in the country, said a survey disclosed today.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of the married men in Shanghai
Municipality spoke highly of their wives with regard to the
handling of family affairs, according to the survey conducted by
the Shanghai Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
About 14.4 percent of the surveyed husbands said that they have
"personal coffers" for emergency uses to avoid disputes with their
wives. Only 3.2 percent of the local husbands complained that
their wives "act arbitrarily".
</P>
<P>
A total of 57.6 percent of the wives said that they do most of
the household chaos, and some 50 percent of them admitted that
their husbands are busier than themselves.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 43.4 percent of the local families, it
is the husband or husband and wife together who decide on daily
expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
