<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- This largest trade and
financial city of China is expected to export 15 billion US
dollars worth-of goods this year, according to the Shanghai
Municipal Government.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's exports reached 13.8 billion dollars in the first 11
months of this year, up 13.8 percent from the same period of last
year, according to the Shanghai Municipal Commission of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises have become a driving force behind
exports, with their exports reaching 4.9 billion dollars during
that period, up 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Pudong New Area has also scored a substantial
increase in exports, with its exports rising 7.44 percent and
accounting nearly one fifth of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
A success has also been made in expanding overseas markets for
Shanghai-made products. Shanghai exported a total of 9.45 billion
dollars worth of products to Hong Kong, Japan, the United States,
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, Shanghai should take measures to improve the quality
of its export commodities, and reform its export growth mode, said
Zhu Xiaoming, director of the Shanghai Municipal Commission of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Next year Shanghai will grant 100 more enterprises the
authority to independently handle imports and exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's exports are projected at 20 billion dollars in the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
