<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Province Has Plenty of Prehistorical Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered even more Early Stone Age relics near the city of
Guiyang, the capital of southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
The discovery brings the number of relics locations in the city
to at least 80, and the earliest date of human inhabitants has
been pushed back another 10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 stone tools and fossilized bone are from the later
Early Stone Age or from early in the Later Stone Age, the
archaeologists said.
</P>
<P>
According to one researcher from the provincial museum,
Guizhou's characteristic karst formations have left many limestone
caves, some of which were used by early man.
</P>
<P>
The prehistorical relics were first discovered in Guanyin cave
in western Guizhou in 1964. Many of the sites have a large number
of relics, and thousands of stone tools have been found in one
place.
</P>
<P>
Six of the sites are under the state-level protection, and 15
others are under provincial-level protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
