<HEADLINE> State Farms in Northeast China Report Good Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Heilongjiang Reclamation
Area, one of the largest groups of state farms in China, harvested
8.5 billion kg of grain and soy beans this year, double the 1994
figure.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of corn and rice to the area's farm produce output
has risen from 15 percent in 1994 to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
A Heilongjiang Provincial Government official attributed the
good harvest to large-scale land improvement and the application
of modern techniques in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The area has invested 3.1 billion yuan improving 666,600 ha
of low- and medium-yield farmland, checking soil erosion on
333,300 ha and undertaking a number of irrigation and seed
processing projects.
</P>
<P>
The drive to spread the use of new techniques in recent year
has raised the average per-ha output of grain and beans to 4,695
kg, 84 percent more than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
So far, 18 agriculture-related enterprise groups have been
formed, with their combined industrial output value expected to
reach 6.2 billion yuan this year, up nearly 50 percent from 1994.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the policy of reforms and opening to the outside
world, the area has approved 25 foreign-funded enterprises
involving 48 million U.S. dollars in overseas funds over the past
three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
