<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest World Bank Project in Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 16 (Xinhua) -- An agricultural project using
World Bank loans to improve farmland has has been completed in
east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6 billion yuan (192.8 million U.S. dollars) project began
in 1991 as the province's largest agricultural project, levelling
184,000 hectares of land, improving 320,000 ha. of low-yielding
land, buying more than 15,400 farm machines, and building 3,477 km
of roads.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 2,100 water stations were set up, 5,400 wells
sunk, and 8,000 wells rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
The project is already having good economic and ecological
effects. Last year, areas around the project area increased grain
output by 1.02 million tons, oil-bearing crops by 117,700 tons,
and cotton by 26,400 tons.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that per-capita income of farmers in these
areas is 1,725 yuan, an increase of 1,348 yuan, and green coverage
in the areas rose by three percent and 59 ecological zones were
set up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
