<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven New Nature Reserves In Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
has established seven new nature reserves to protect rare animal
species and preserve the environment, four in mountainous areas,
and the rest in wetlands.
</P>
<P>
The mountain reserves are at Jiulingshan, Yangling, Shuijiang,
and Yunjushan on a total of 15,829 hectares of land, which are
home to 20 species of rare wild animals and birds and more than 30
plants and trees.
</P>
<P>
The wetlands are at Yuanyang, Nanjishan, and Qinglan lakes, on
35,217 hectares of land, which have birds like mandrain ducks,
white cranes, storks, swans, and white-forehead geese.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiangxi's Environmental Protection Department, the
new preserves bring the number of nature reserves in Jiangxi to 15
and the total area to 400,000 hectares, or 7.8 percent of
province's total area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
