<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, ASEAN Pledge Close Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and leaders of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) Tuesday agreed to enhance cooperation between China and
ASEAN as well as between China and individual ASEAN member states.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued following their meeting, Jiang and
leaders of the nine ASEAN countries agreed that consolidation of
the cooperation between China and ASEAN serves the interests of
their people as well as peace, stability and prosperity in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders decided to heighten cooperation at bilateral and
multilateral levels in promoting economic growth, sustainable
development and social progress on the basis of equality and
mutual benefit, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to enhance cooperation at the ASEAN Regional Forum
and other regional and international organizations and fora.
</P>
<P>
China and ASEAN would intensify cooperation through mechanisms
such as the ASEAN-China Joint Cooperation Committee, the
ASEAN-China joint Committee on Economic and Trade Cooperation and
the ASEAN-China Joint Committee on Science and Technology
Cooperation in regional organizations or projects, it said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also reaffirmed their common interest in developing
the Mekong Basin and pledged to strengthen their support for the
riparian countries by promoting activities in the areas of trade,
tourism and transport.
</P>
<P>
They pledged support for universality of World Trade
Organization membership and for the early entry of China and ASEAN
applicants to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
At their meeting, the leaders also endorsed the Finance
Ministers' agreement, reached in Kuala Lumpur on December 2, 1997,
on the rapid implementation of the Manila Framework as a
constructive step towards promoting financial stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
They encouraged efforts to carry forward the initiatives under
the Manila Framework and work closely with the International
Monetary Fund, World Bank, Asian Development Bank and
international regulatory bodies.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
