<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Announces Plan of Golden Jubilee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government
today announced its plan of celebrations for the country's 50th
Independence Day, which falls on February 4, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The main ceremony will be held in the central mountain city of
Kandy, Sri Lanka's ancient capital, to mark the 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga, government officials and
foreign dignitaries will go to Kandy to witness the celebrations
there, which will start on February 3 and end on the 5th.
</P>
<P>
Religious activities, parade of the three armed services and
the police and cultural performances will be conducted on the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
Public Administration and Home Affairs Minister Ratnasiri
Wickramanayake told a press conference this morning that
simultaneous celebrations will also be held throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Colombo, a grand exhibition will be held
from February 5 to 20 to highlight the progress Sri Lanka has
achieved since its independence in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Major cities in Sri Lanka, including Colombo and Kandy, will be
decorated for the Golden Jubilee celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The minister said roads in Kandy will be widened and upgraded
and stadiums and schools in the city will be repaired to prepare
for the event.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated a sum of 300 million rupees (5
million U.S. dollars) for the celebrations, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that security will be tight to ensure there will be no
sabotage from separatists during the celebrations. Roads to Kandy
will be blocked at 7 p.m. on February 3 to this effect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
