<HEADLINE> Thailand to Reduce Number of New Drug Addicts: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister's Office
Minister Jurin Laksanavisit said on Monday that the government
plans to reduce the number of new drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
Jurin said if the plan is successful and the number of new
addicts are reduced, drug traffickers will have difficulty finding
customers and the drug trade would die "a natural death."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the drug situation in the country has worsened
this year and that the economic crisis has forced otherwise
law-abiding people into making fast and dirty money through
selling drugs.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, police have stepped up the crackdown on
teenager drug abuse. In the past month alone, police arrested 128
teenagers who tested drug positive, in raids on two night spots
where hundreds of teenagers were holding what are known as "drug
parties."
</P>
<P>
Police are in particular watchful for youngsters' birthday
parties, where teenager drug addicts sometimes gather.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy interior minister Vatana Asavahame said on
Monday that the country lacks prison space for the 140,000
inmates, of which 40,000 are drug offenders, the largest group of
inmates in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry plans to spend 50 million baht (1.1
million U.S. dollars) to convert a number of former Vietnamese
refugee centers in the northeast province of Nakhon Ratchasima
into a prison for drug convicts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
