<HEADLINE> Support Rate for New Zealand Government Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Support for the New Zealand
coalition government has increased after Jenny Shipley took over
as prime minister early this month, a latest poll revealed.
</P>
<P>
The result of the TVNZ-Colomar Brunton poll, which was released
on Monday evening, showed that disapproval rate of the government
had dropped to 80 percent, the lowest since April, while the
approval rate for the government had risen to 12 percent, twice of
that before Shipley became prime minister on December 8.
</P>
<P>
Shipley's rating as the preferred prime minister was up four
percentage points to 27 percent, only one point behind Labor
leader Helen Clark, whose rating slid four points to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Support for the National Party also climbed four points to 40
percent, the highest since April. But it was still lower than
Labor's 46 percent.  
</P>
