<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies Employ Child Labor in Fields and Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- About 123,000 children aged
14-17 work in America's fields, according to an unreleased Labor
Department survey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 13,100 children worked illegally last year
in garment industry sweatshops -- factories that repeatedly
violate federal wages and hours laws, according to study
commissioned by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Many of America's working children are not the ones you see.
They are not the teen-agers who flame-broil Double Whoppers at
Burger King or bag groceries at Food Lion, though they are
governed by the same laws, said an AP report.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal law bars children under 16 from working while
school is in session. Outside school hours, anyone 14 or 15 may
work in farm jobs that the U.S. Labor Department deems safe.
Younger children, those 12 or 13, can work only on farms and at a
few other specific jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many of the children working in America are frequently
underpaid, often unaccompanied and largely unprotected -- a shadow
generation made prematurely adult, moving from coast to coast,
border to border.
</P>
<P>
Some kids want spending money to buy into the consumer culture
they see as necessary to being American. But many, especially
migrant children, work because their parents don't earn enough.
</P>
<P>
"If adults were paid a living wage, we wouldn't have child
labor," Ann Millard, a Michigan State University anthropologist
who studies migrant labor, as saying. Three out of four migrant
families say they earn 5,000 dollars or less yearly according to a
national database of 54,000 families compiled by a farmworker
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
In some Manhattan garment shops, children eat lunch in dank,
urine-soaked stairwells. Others sleep in overcrowded apartments or
houses. Pennsylvania mushroom picker Rigoberto Rosales, 17, shares
a house with more than 25 other Mexicans and carves a certain
privacy for himself by erecting a cardboard box around his bare
mattress, the report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Delegation visits Belarus to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MINSK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Belarus's Prime Minister Sergei
Ling said Sunday that Belarus plans to cooperate with the United
States based on the principles of "equality and mutual benefit."
</P>
<P>
Ling made the remark during the U.S. delegation's visit to
Belarus. He stressed that enhancing foreign cooperation is crucial
to the country's economy, and Belarus has an open economy, with
two thirds of its production exported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation, headed by Steven Sestanovich, who is a
special counselor for the Secretary of State, made a one-day visit
to Belarus on Sunday. The two countries expressed hopes to
overcome the obstacles between them through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Ling emphasized that Belarus has played a "role of stability"
in eastern Europe. Belarus will seek to resolve all problems with
the U.S. through "the way of civilization," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States is an important trade partner of Belarus. The
trade volume between them in 1996 reached 212 million
U.S. dollars, up 45 per cent compared to the same period in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Belarus established diplomatic relation with the U.S. on
December 28, 1991, since then more than 20 documents of
cooperation have been signed between them. But bilateral relations
on politics has met with some trouble recently, due to problems
such as the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
