<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economy Sees Recovery: Chubais </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia's financial situation,
seriously influenced by the recent international financial crisis,
is starting to improve, first deputy Prime Minister Anatoly
Borisovich Chubais said today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The most threatening period to the Russian economy is finally
over, Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
The bond interest rate in Russia's financial market continues
to decline, while stock prices have maintained growth momentum
since early December, Chubais said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Chubais said, the Russian government is
paying close attention to future changes in the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Russia's inflation rate will exceed the estimated figure to
reach 11 percent, with a 1 percent increase occurring in December,
Chubais predicted.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998 is expected to grow by
2 percent, which means the Russian government could overcome the
financial turmoil in the end, the deputy prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will no longer need new credits from foreign banks from
this December to January next year, Chubais indicated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chubais doesn't rule out the possibility of getting
a loan worth 2 billion U.S. dollars from the West's four major
banks.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government will also pay off the default wages of
the workers, Chubais added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
