<HEADLINE> Canada Extends Immigration Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said today
it has extended its current immigration investor program for another
year.
</P>
<P>
The program has been given authority to run until December 31,
1998, Minister of Citizenship and Immigration Lucienne Robillard
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Introduced 10 years ago in Canada, the program was intended to lure
rich immigrants, especially those from Asia, to the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, immigrants can obtain a visa here if they invest
a minimum 350,000 dollars (245,000 USD) in rich provinces such as
Ontario and 250,000 dollars in poor ones.
</P>
<P>
It has been criticized by some as a way of buying into the country.
And investors has complained of mismanagement of the investment funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
