<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Remove Large Tumor From Man's Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A 5.5 kg malignant tumor on the
bone of a young man's left leg was removed recently by doctors at
the Xijing Hospital in Xi'an, the capital of northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Fusheng, 25, from the city of Qinhuangdao in north China's
Hebei Province had asked many large hospitals to help him, but
they refused because of the size of the tumor for the fear that
the operation would be too risky, and suggested that the leg be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
By the time the man began to receive treatment at Xijing
Hospital in November, the tumor was 80 cm. in circumference and he
was given six days of chemotherapy before the operation.
</P>
<P>
The chief surgeon, Wang Zhen, explained that after the tumor
was entirely removed, the bone was replaced with a metal alloy
used for artificial limbs.
</P>
<P>
The ten-hour operation saved both the leg and the patient's
life, and he is in satisfactory condition.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said that the hospital has performed about 50 such
operations, but that the size of the tumor was quite rare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
