<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Reserves Above IMF-Required Minimum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign reserves
stood at 26.3 billion U.S. dollars in November after dropping 2.1
billion dollars in the last two weeks of the month, the Bank of
Thailand said Monday.
</P>
<P>
At 26.3 billion dollars, Thailand's foreign reserves were the
lowest since August, when reserves stood at 35.9 billion dollars.
But they were well above the minimum of 23 billion dollar Thailand
must maintain this year to meet the International Monetary Fund
(IMF)'s requirement.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign reserves had been swelled in recent months
by drawing on a 17.2 billion dollar bailout fund organized by the
IMF for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand Monday said it settled forward-currency
obligations totaling 2.1 billion dollars in the last two weeks of
November, bringing its net forward obligations down to 18.3
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
These obligations were incurred as a result of the Thai central
bank's interventions early this year to defend the baht against
speculators. The defense was abandoned on July 2 when the baht was
floated. Since then, the baht's value has been on the decline
against the U.S. dollar. On the day before the float, the mid-rate
was 25.79 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Monday, the Thai currency lost 2.75 baht in a single day to hit
an all-time low of 48.10 to the dollar in local spot trading. The
Bank of Thailand set the reference rate Monday at 44.99 to the
dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
