<HEADLINE> Venezuela Swears In New Minister of Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Freddy Rojas Parra was sworn in as
the new Minister of Finance in Venezuela, replacing the outgoing
Minister Luis Raul Matos Azocar.
</P>
<P>
Rojas Parra was the Minister of Industry and Foreign Commerce
before he was appointed to his new post by President Rafael
Caldera.
</P>
<P>
Caldera said at the swearing in ceremony that Freddy Rojas has
always been devoted to the arduous task of managing the country`s
economy.
</P>
<P>
Matos Azocar stepped down on December 11. Azocar said in his
written resignation that his action was to avoid further
confrontation between the executive and the legislative branches.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the heavy criticism that a minority
parliamentary group had cast upon him. The group was also
proposing a vote of censorship against him in the Congress.
</P>
<P>
President Caldera accepted -- on that same day -- Azocar's
resignation while praising him for his three years of hard work as
Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
The head of state described as "unjust" the campaign that had
been conducted against Matos Azocar.
</P>
<P>
The Congress accused the former Minister of having committed
fraud against the country. He allegedly used 9.47 million dollars
of federal funds to pay an Italian company Samana.
</P>
<P>
The motion of censorship charged Matos Azocar with negligence
and concealment because he allegedly ordered the suspension of a
probe in the case. 
</P>
