<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned by French Role in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Monday it would be deeply concerned if French troops were not fully
carrying out their responsibilities to arrest war crimes suspects
in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Louise Arbour, the chief prosecutor of the Yugoslav war crimes
tribunal, had said French forces have refused to testify against
or arrest suspected war criminals.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at press briefing, U.S. State Department spokesman
James Foley said U.S. officials were aware of Arbour's remarks but
had not had an opportunity to assess them.
</P>
<P>
But Foley said he expects that France and other countries with
troops in the area will detain war crimes suspects if they
encounter them.
</P>
<P>
The Stabilization Force (SFOR) troops in Bosnia, including the
French and Americans, were authorized to arrest those war crime
suspects, including former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
when they met them. 
</P>
