<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Rejects House Panel Demand for Independent Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno rejected on Monday a Congress' demand for an immediate
independent counsel probe to investigate President Bill Clinton
over the denial of a casino license to Indian tribes in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Reno, however, reminded Republicans that a separate ongoing
investigation of Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt could lead to an
independent investigation of the same activity.
</P>
<P>
The Republican demand for an independent investigation of the
president centers on allegations that Babbitt, on orders from the
White House, denied a casino application for poor Indian tribes in
Wisconsin because rival tribes in Minnesota opposed it. The rival
tribes also sponsor gambling and contributed heavily to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Reno sent a letter Monday to House Judiciary Chairman Henry
Hyde, a Republican, giving her reasons for rejecting the
Republican demand. Hyde and other Republicans on the committee had
sent a letter to Reno on November 13 putting forward what they
believed was cause for an independent probe of the president.
</P>
<P>
Reno was required by law to answer the letter Monday.
</P>
<P>
In her letter to Hyde, Reno said that the letter from
congressional Republicans "points to allegations that...lobbyists
for Indian tribes opposed to the casino application allegedly
mentioned the...issue to President Clinton..."
</P>
<P>
Reno wrote, "We are also aware of other evidence that the
president was aware of and inquired of his staff about the status
of the casino matter, and are aware that some White House staff
were monitoring the matter and inquiring of the Department of
Interior concerning it."
</P>
<P>
But Reno concluded, "Information that the president was aware
of a regulatory matter under review by an executive branch agency
does not, however, in and of itself indicate criminal wrongdoing
by the president."
</P>
<P>
The attorney general's rejection of the Hyde demand does not
affect a separate 90-day investigation into allegations against
Babbitt in the matter. That probe could lead to an independent
counsel, and ends February 11.
</P>
<P>
Hyde said today, "How much longer the spirit and letter of the
independent counsel law can be ignored by the nation's chief law
enforcement officer is an increasingly critical question."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
