<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur to Accelerate Integration Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, December 15 (XINHUA) -- Presidents of the member
countries of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) today vowed to
strengthen the process of political, economic, financial, social,
cultural and scientific integration.
</P>
<P>
The commitment was made at the 13th Summit of Mercosur closed
earlier today by presidents of Argentina, Paraguay, Brazil,
Uruguay, Bolivia and Chile.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique the presidents underlined their
willingness to continue the process of setting up Mercosur
according to a model of "opened regionalism," congruent to the
norms of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The joint communique said that three years after the
implementation of the customs unification, Mercosur was capable of
meeting challenges generated by the dynamics of integration.
</P>
<P>
The presidents expressed their satisfaction to the efficiency
of their respective governments in taking measures to lessen the
impact of the financial turmoil in Asia through consultation and
coordination.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the importance of democracy as a necessary
condition for cooperation in Mercosur and underlined the
importance of cooperation in the scientific field in order to
prevent the brain drain.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the presidents talked about the increment of
common taxes to third countries, the general anti-dumping law,
social security and the full participation of Chile in the bloc.
</P>
<P>
They ratified the progressive and eventually total
liberalization of services in a 10-year term. They also approved
the norms for common rules regarding measures against dumping
imports from other countries.
</P>
<P>
They reached an agreement on social security, which will give
the full recognization of the rights of workers and their families
to social security, and set up a similar legal frame in each
member country.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur members include Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, with Chile and Bolivia being associated members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
