<HEADLINE> Forest Fires in Indonesia cause heavy Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Forest fires this year in
Indonesia have destroyed more than 165,000 hectares of forest,
causing an estimated loss of 132 billion rupiah (26.4 million U.S.
dollars), a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Forest burning also damaged the soil as it killed all the
useful microorganisms which made the land productive," Minister of
Forestry Djamaludin Suryohadikusumo said in Karang Joang, East
Kalimantan, Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figure did not include the financial losses of timber
estates and plantation companies, local press today quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The forest fires, which started from mid August this year in
Sumatra, Kalimantan, Java and Irian Jaya islands, have also caused
haze in the country as well as in Malaysia and Singapore. The haze
have affected the health of more than 20 million people in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"It will take a very long time and a lot of money to
rehabilitate the damaged soil," said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
