<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD, IMF Say Italy Will Meet Euro Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Italy will successfully cut its
budget deficit to 3 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) as
required for the European single currency, the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said in an annual
report today.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
confirmed that Italy will not require supplementary budgets for
1997 in a report presented today to Italian Bank Governor and
Economic Minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the OECD, Italy's GDP will rise by 1.3 percent by
the end of 1997, but will not show an exceptional rise in 1998,
even if investments and exports increase.
</P>
<P>
GDP growth should come in around 2 percent in 1998, the OECD
report said.
</P>
<P>
This modest rise will result in marginal reductions in
unemployment levels, which are expected to fall from 12.3 percent
at the end of 1997 to 12.2 percent in 1998 and 12 percent in 1999,
the same as the rate in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The OECD noted a decrease in Italy's long-term interest rates
after the Bank of Italy lowered discount rate last June, strongly
raising Italy's chances of entering the EMU as a first-round
participant.
</P>
<P>
Lower interest rates and the one-off "Euro-tax" helped Italy to
reach its 3 percent budget deficit goal in 1997 for joining the
Euro, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the IMF gave Italy's finance a vote of confidence
today when it announced that the country would not need a
supplementary budget.
</P>
<P>
"Italy has come a long way," the IMF delegation's
second-in-command Alessansdro Leipold said today at the end of its
two-week study. "But now it shouldn't slow down." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's Island Province Has Gene Bank For Rare Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's island province of
Hainan has just built a 15-hectare gene bank for rare tropical
trees in the town of Fengmu in Tunchang County, to help protect
rare species.
</P>
<P>
The gene bank has 800 different species of trees and shrubs, 70
of which are found only in Hainan, and 60 of which are endangered
ones. An example is Hainan sindora clabra, a very rare tree
which is believed to be effective in treating blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has 1,400 species of trees and shrubs overall, or 28
percent of the total number in China, 458 of which are under state
protection, and some of which are on the verge of extinction,
according to the Hainan Forestry Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Although trees have gradually been replaced by other materials
in ship-building or things like handicrafts, their role in the
ecology or in medicine is irreplaceable, the institute says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
