<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls, Stocks Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah and
loccal stock prices continued their uncontrolled free falls Monday
due to weak regional currencies and lingering unfounded rumors,
dealers and stockbrokers said today.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which opened at 4,900/5,100 against the U.S. dollar
in the spot market, fell almost 16 percent to a record low of
5,800 and closed at 5,600/5,900.
</P>
<P>
Stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange lost 7.2 percent,
with the composite index closed down 26.317 points at 339.536.
</P>
<P>
Clear signals that President Soeharto had begun to gradually
return to work Monday after rest on medical advice failed to
impress the currency market, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
"People are really losing confidence in the rupiah as they
continue to buy dollars at the current rate, which is believed to
be too expensive," a local bank dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers said if the rupiah continued to weaken or stay at
the current level, it would push more companies toward bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 100 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar since early this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
