<HEADLINE> Fresh Fish Come To Remote Chinese Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Fresh fish are now available
in the diets of ordinary folk living on the Loess Highland of
north China's Shanxi Province, something that was seldom seen in
the past.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the fish business has become quite profitable in the
arid province, which now has about 20,000 ha of ponds for raising
fish.
</P>
<P>
The province has established 40 state-run fish farms, and
farmers have added about 500 more, providing 20,000 tons of fish
annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition to ponds and reservoirs, farmers are using areas
along the Yellow and Fenhe rivers. And by using technology, the
varieties of fish have gone from half a dozen to more than a
dozen. More important, carps now provide more than 80 percent of
the province's aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, soft-shelled turtles and shrimps have also
become available in local markets.
</P>
<P>
Government officials attribute all this to improvements in
local people's standard of living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
