<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Prime Minister to Visit China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko will make a five-day official visit to China on
December 22 to help forge economic links with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine and China have expressed the wish to conduct
cooperation in many areas," said Pustovoitenko, who will lead a
delegation of about 30 officials and businessmen. "The main
objective of my visit is to find ways and means to cooperate."
</P>
<P>
He added that the two nations will sign a declaration on
enhancing trade, investment and science cooperation, an agreement
on tariff matters and a protocol on military technology
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Since China and Ukraine established diplomatic relations in
January 1994, trade volume between the two countries has increased
slowly, reaching 955 million U.S. dollars in the first nine months
of 1997, a 109 million dollar increase since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has also enjoyed a surplus of 781 million dollars
during the first nine months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Its major exports to China are mostly raw materials including
metals and fertilizers, Pustovoitenko said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that Ukrainian tractors, harvesters,
excavators, planes and fishing boats could win a comfortable
market share in China.
</P>
<P>
"Bilateral trade is growing, but there is still a lot of room
for improvement," the Ukrainian prime minister said. He said he
hoped the trade turnover between the two countries could increase
to five or six billion U.S. dollars before 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
