<HEADLINE> Art Education in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Primary and middle
schools in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
have started teaching calligraphy, painting, drama and sculpture
as well as how to play musical instruments and chess, which used
to be taught only in artistic schools.
</P>
<P>
The educational sector in Guangzhou has emphasized the arts in
recent years. Primary and middle schools in the four old districts
in the city all set up the art courses. About 95 percent of
schools in other districts established art courses as well.
</P>
<P>
Schools at the town level all have full-time teachers with a
university education to teach music and fine arts classes.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Guangzhou Education Commission said: "Art
education, as an important content of the quality of education,
will help develop the intelligence of the students and,
therefore, it is welcomed by the parents."
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of art courses, students have become
more active and get higher exam scores in language and math,
according to the dean in Xianjidong Primary School in Liwan
District.
</P>
<P>
So far, 10 outstanding teachers in the city have won titles in
nationwide music and fine arts competitions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
