<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving Workers' Quality Crucial To Finding New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Finding employment for workers
who have lost their jobs largely has to do with personal
qualities, according to an article in today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, workers with university education
account for only two percent of the Chinese labor force. About 30
percent of the new workers in recent years have never received any
vocational training, and only half of the 140 million urban
workers have higher technical skills, while two-thirds have basic
technical skills, the story said.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Beijing Labor Bureau found that 6.23
percent of laid off people have vocational training, and 38
percent of in-service workers have training.
</P>
<P>
In job applications filled out for a Shanghai company, 67.9
percent of the laid-off people said they can only do physical
labor.
</P>
<P>
In China's re-employment projects, many government offices
concentrate on providing job opportunities, and not on improving
workers' quality. Statistics show that 1.6 million laid-off people
received training in recent years, but more than one million
workers needed new jobs every year from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing, however, is changing unemployed
workers' attitudes about re-employment.
</P>
<P>
A women's vocational education center in Shanghai helped build
confidence among its trainees, most of whom had been laid off, and
China will promote re-employment through practical and regular
training, according to Zhang Xiaojian, a Ministry of Labor
director.
</P>
<P>
The country will support training projects for ten million
unemployed people from 1996 to 2000, the story said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
