<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Control of Dumping At Sea to Be Tightened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's State oceanographic
Administration (SOA) is to strengthen supervision of the dumping
of rubbish in the ocean, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
It has decided to introduce a system of recording apparatus on
ships dumping waste.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 50 million cubic metres of solid waste is
discharged each year into the oceans. If each ship were to carry
700 cubic metres on average, there would be more than 70,000 ships
dumping garbage into the sea.
</P>
<P>
In recent decades, the SOA has invested much money, equipment
and personnel in improving the management of ocean-dumping
activities, according to an SOA official.
</P>
<P>
The official said the country had designated special areas for
dumping garbage, and there were regulations on dumping at sea
under the country's Oceanic Environmental Protection Law.
</P>
<P>
To effectively implement the regulations, the SOA and its
branches nationwide have organized technical training for relevant
monitoring and supervision personnel, drawn up management
regulations on the method of implementing a system for recording
dumping at sea.
</P>
<P>
Under the system which will take effect on january 1 next year,
dumping recording machines must be installed on ships before
application can be made to the SOA for dumping certificates, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
The recording apparatus will keep a full record of the
navigation routes of ships dumping waste, thus preventing them
entering undesignated areas, and better protecting the ocean
environment and maritime resources, he said.
</P>
<P>
A set of preliminary regulations on the use of equipment
recording the course of dumping ships in the Yellow Sea and Bohai
Bay came into effect on November 19 this year.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate that ships designated for dumping in
these two seas must install navigation recording apparatus
approved by the SOA, otherwise the ships will lose their dumping
certificates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Provides "Green Cards" to Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-three laid-off workers
in Lengshuijiang, a city in central-south China's Hunan Province,
started selling snacks on Jinzhu West Road, converting it to a
well-known "Food Street."
</P>
<P>
These workers, who had been laid off from state-owned
enterprises, are the first to receive "green cards" from the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Issuing "green cards" is one concrete measure taken by local
government in the city's re-employment efforts.
</P>
<P>
The green cards are actually accommodation papers given to
the laid-off workers who have difficulty in supporting themselves.
</P>
<P>
With the papers, cardholders can be self-employed laborers who
enjoy simple formalities and preferential policies from industrial
and commercial, public health and environmental protection sectors.
</P>
<P>
Each year, cardholders pay 1,000-to-3,000 yuan less. Because
the cover is green, laid-off workers call them "green cards".
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhenxi, a green-card holder, said: "All of us are quite
satisfied with it."
</P>
<P>
Lengshuijiang, an important energy and raw material center in
Hunan Province, has more than 50 state-owned enterprises and 7,000
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The city government has issue 500 green cards since March this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libraries Making Gains in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region,
which is home to 2.4 million people, currently has about 60
libraries with a total of one million books.
</P>
<P>
The earliest library after the liberation of Tibet was founded
in 1952 on the basis of an army reading room. In 1958, the first
formal library in Tibet was established, which became the library
of the Tibet Institute for Nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Following that, a number of libraries were established by
research institutes, institutions of higher learning and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
In May of 1995 the Tibet Library, at a cost of 18.43 million
yuan (2.2 million U.S. dollars), became the first regional library
accessible to the general public.
</P>
<P>
The modern library has seven reading rooms with 300 seats, and
the books are catalogued in both Tibetan and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Libraries and publishing houses, and individuals as well, have
been active in donating books to the Tibet Library, now the
biggest in Tibet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Industry to be One of China's Leading Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The development of marine
resources is expected to become a leading industry in China in the
next century, according to a national conference held here.
</P>
<P>
China has expanded its marine industries from fisheries,
salt-making and shipping to offshore oil, tourism and chemical
development.
</P>
<P>
The country has also made progress in developing new marine
industries, such as the desalination of sea water, the development
of sea pharmaceuticals and health food, and the use of marine
energy, plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
The output value of the country's marine industry rose from
43.9 billion yuan in 1990 to more than 246 billion yuan in 1995,
with the annual growth rate surpassing 20 percent, faster than the
growth rate of the national economy. By 2000, the output value is
expected to hit 550 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
As the leading sector of the marine industry, the country's
fisheries contribute 48 percent of the marine industry's value and
had more than 20 million tons in output last year.
</P>
<P>
During the 1990-1995 period, the country's shipping grew at an
annual rate of 24 percent, while offshore tourism increased by 33
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
