<HEADLINE> Vieira Disappointed with Iranian Football Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The temporary head coach of
Iranian National football team Brazilian Valdeir Vieira has
expressed his disappointment to the attitude of Iranian football
officials towards him after the Iranian team obtained the entry
permission to the World Cup 1998 under his guidance.
</P>
<P>
"I found it disappointing when the same people who said to me
that if we qualified, I would go to France were now looking for
other people," Vieira said in an interview with Iran News
published today.
</P>
<P>
Vieira was chosen by head of the Iranian Football Federation as
head coach of the Iranian national football team after Iran was
defeated by Qatar. The Iranian team was qualified for the World
Cup 1998 after it drew the Australian team in Melbourne with 2-2.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't ask for money or anything else but asked for being
kept with the team and go to France if we qualified for the World
Cup finals," Vieira said, and the Iranian football federation
made the promise.
</P>
<P>
He criticized Iranian football officials for their manners with
him, saying that "probably many people here would like to have a
coach they could use like a puppet," but "I have my own principles
and don't let anybody to interfere in my work."
</P>
<P>
Vieira believed that he could promote the capabilities of the
Iranian football if he would stay as its head coach, saying that
the Iranian players play from their very hearts but they use only
20 percent of their brains.
</P>
<P>
"So what I want to do is to extend this brain participation to
40 percent," he added.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the reports that he would find a job in the United
States, saying that "I have some offers at hand but I assure that
America is not in our plans." 
</P>
</TEXT>
