<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friendship Booms between Chinese, Foreign Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- During the last 24 years, 200
Chinese cities have formed more than 800 pairs of sister city
relationships with foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
In 1973 Tianjin formed China's first sister city relationship
with Kobe, Japan, according to a recent meeting on China's
friendly exchanges with foreign countries, which was held in the
capital city of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
"At that time (such a relationship) implied heavy official
approval, but now the forming of sister cities serves as a major
channel for non-governmental relations," said Bi Huiluo, an
official with the Chinese People's Association for Friendship with
Foreign Countries.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 80 percent of such Chinese cities are located in
the economically booming coastal areas, with Jiangsu and Shandong
provinces accommodating the most.
</P>
<P>
However, with improvements in transportation and investment
conditions in the country's central and western areas, more cities
in wider areas are establishing sister city relationships.
</P>
<P>
Sister cities have enhanced mutual understanding and
friendship, and fostered exchanges and cooperations in industry,
agriculture, economy and trade, and cultural and educational
undertakings, Bi said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 600 trading exhibitions were
held across China during the last five years, with an overall
transaction volume of 6 billion U.S. dollars and nearly 10 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign investment introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
