<HEADLINE> HK New Airport Marathon Set for Runway Finish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Amateur
Athletic Association (HKAAA) announced here today that it will
organize an international marathon race next February, which will
finish at Hong Kong's New Airport at Chek Lap Kok, Lantau.
</P>
<P>
The HKAAA joined forces with Standard Chartered Bank, the New
Airport Projects Coordination Office and the Airport Authority to
announce that its annual marathon will make a historic departure
from its cross-border tradition to commemorate the new airport
project.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Chartered '98 New Airport Marathon on February 22,
 1998, is expected to attract a record-breaking field of more than
 7,000 local and international athletes, including top-class
runners from Kenya, Canada, Britain, New Zealand, the United
States, China, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
That would make it the largest ever athletic event in Hong
Kong, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The marathon race will be one of the public events leading to
the opening of the new airport.
</P>
<P>
From the eastern end of the Tsing Ma Bridge - the world's
longest road-rail suspension bridge at 1,377 meters, across Lantau
 Island to the end of the new airport runway, the course of the
1998 race will set a spectacular new standard for staging
world-class marathon, HKAAA officials said.
</P>
<P>
Since the first Hong Kong-Shenzhen race in 1992, the marathon
has consistently attracted a strong international field. Next
year's race, the first since Hong Kong's handover on July 1, goes
beyond the traditional focus with its landmark setting at the new
airport, Hong Kong's future gateway to the world, according to the
 organizers.
</P>
<P>
And, in addition to the grueling challenge of a full-length
marathon, a shorter, 10-kilometer race will also be staged and
contested along the new airport's runway.
</P>
<P>
On May 4 this year, an international marathon race was staged
from the Tsing Ma Bridge, which is one of the projects of the
overall New Airport Program, and attracted a field of 1,000
runners from home and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
