<TEXT>
<P>
"National Interest" Investments Rise In Uruguay
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Investments in projects regarded as of "national
interest" for Uruguay rose to 268.5 million dollars over the first
10 months, an increment of 70 million dollars with respect to the
total invested in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A report of the Uruguay`S Chamber of Industry said that out of
30 projects considered of national importance for Uruguay, 17 were
carried out in the state of Montevideo with 163.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brazil`S International Monetary Reserves Drop
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian international monetary reserves shrank
over November to 51.17 billion dollars, the lowest level since
December 1995, reported the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The amount means a reduction of 1.67 billion dollars out of the
52.85 billion dollars left in October.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was due to the measures adopted to face the
negative fallout caused by the late finance crisis in Asia,
according to the institution.
</P>
<P>
The bank said international reserves will recover fast. Just in
the first eight days of December, reserves had gained 925 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports Of Brazil To MERCOSUR Boost
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazilian exports to its Southern Common
Market (MERCOSUR) partner countries amounted to 8.25 billion
dollars from January to November, a 23.58 percent rise against the
same period 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat of Foreign Commerce said that Argentina is the
main target of Brazilian products with 6.18 billion dollars worth
of products shipped, a 6.71 percent increase against 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sales Of Electric Household Appliances Soar In Venezuela
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The market of electric household appliances in
Venezuela grew 35 percent in 1997, which means that so far this
year some 900,000 appliances were sold, against 665,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela`S Chamber of Electric and Electronic Appliances
Manufacturers reported that 70 percent of the demand was met by
national producers, while imports contributed 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fishing Skyrocketed In Mexico
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The fishing sector in Mexico registered a growth
of 4.8 percent in production and rose by 3.2 percent its
contribution to the national domestic product (NDP), a better rate
than that obtained by the entire economy over the first 10 months
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary of Environment, Natural Resources and Fishing,
Julia Carabias said that this year may be the most productive in
the history of the sector, with a projected fishing of 600.000
tons. 
</P>
