<HEADLINE> Irish Prime Minister Predicts Peace Accord by March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern said today that there will be a new political deal for the
British-run province of Northern Ireland by March.
</P>
<P>
The draft of an agreement would include provision for a new
assembly and political linkups involving parliamentarians from all
the parties involved, said Ahern after a 50-minute meeting with
U.S. President Bill Clinton at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, optimistic after getting full support from
Clinton, said all sides to the dispute had to make compromises in
order to reach a balanced settlement.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking to reporters after the meeting, Clinton said he
would remain "personally involved in this," and Ahern called him
central to the process.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to stay personally involved in this in whatever way
I can be helpful. I will do anything I can," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Ahern told reporters that he expected parties to the talks to
agree on an agenda of key issues and lay out a format for
addressing it before the Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland have set a deadline in May next year for a
settlement on the dispute over Northern Ireland between
pro-British Protestant and pro-Irish Catholic parties in order to
end the conflict on the province.
</P>
<P>
"There are difficult, difficult decisions that have to be
made, but that's what people who occupy positions of leadership
are hired to do, and the time to do it is now," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between Protestants, most of whom want the
province to remain part of Britain, and Catholics who want
unification with Ireland, has killed more than 3,000 people since
1969.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Northern Ireland Office of Britain announced
that parties to the peace talks for the first time have agreed to
meet in London on January 26 and in Dublin on February 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
