<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homelessness, Food Requests Grow in US Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Demands for emergency food
and shelter are continuing to increase despite the booming
national economy and low unemployment, according to a report
released by the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing this year that a rising tide doesn't lift all
boats," said Joseph Riley Jr., mayor of Charleston, South
Carolina, and chairman of the task force on hunger and
homelessness for the mayors' organization. "Some aren't seaworthy,
others leak and others have persistent problems that require
support."
</P>
<P>
However, there is one positive note in the study -- that
requests for emergency housing rose this year by just 3 percent,
the smallest increase in the survey's 13-year history.
</P>
<P>
But demand for emergency food rose an average of 16 percent,
the largest increase since 1992. Low wages and high housing costs
were among the factors cited for the surge in grocery requests.
Nearly all the cities expected demand for food and shelter to rise
next year.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on self-reporting by 29 cities, found:
</P>
<P>
-- Emergency food assistance requests increased in 24 of the 29
cities surveyed;
</P>
<P>
-- About one-fifth of emergency food requests were estimated to
have gone unfulfilled;
</P>
<P>
-- Seventeen of the cities saw shelter requests rise, while the
number of emergency shelter beds among all the cities decreased an
average of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Charleston, South Carolina, was cited as a success in reducing
the ranks of the homeless.
</P>
<P>
More common in the report, however, are tales of reduced bed
spaces and tougher eligibility requirements in some homeless
shelters.
</P>
<P>
Of the homeless population, about 47 percent are single men, 36
percent families with children, 14 percent single women and 4
percent minors, the survey found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Supports Turkey's EU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States, reacting
to a decision of the European Union not to accept Turkey as a new
member, said today that Turkey is in Europe and should be in the
EU.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a briefing, U.S. State Department spokesman James
Foley tried to play down the gravity of the dispute, in which both
sides are Washington's close allies.
</P>
<P>
"This may have been a setback in recent days.... We would not
want to draw definitive conclusions from what happened last week,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that Turkey's place is in Europe.... We believe
that Turkey ought to have a strong and open perspective on
membership of the EU and we hope that progress can be achieved on
the road," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The EU, citing human rights, the treatment of minority Kurds,
the Cyprus dispute and cultural differences as obstacles to
Turkish membership, last week decided not to put Turkey on the
formal list of potential candidates for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
However, Cyprus, the greater part of which is run by Greek
Cypriots hostile toward Ankara, is on the list.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to cut its ties with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Foley said EU membership for Cyprus could promote the search
for a settlement on the Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
"The EU accession process offers positive incentives for a
Cyprus solution. And in this regard we take note of the EU
summit's statement language that favors Turkish-Cypriot community
participation in the accession talks," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Living Tissues Have Been Grown in Space: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- For the first time, full
living tissues from cartilage-like cells have been grown in
near-zero gravity aboard the Russian Mir station, the Washington
Post reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Although the tissues were viable, but smaller, weaker and more
spherical than its equivalents cultivated on Earth, wrote Lisa E.
Freed, of the Harvard-MIT Division of Health Science and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
Astronaut researchers on board the Mir station last year
isolated several million calf cartilage cells and planted them on
meshes of suture material inside a bioreactor, which kept the
cells supplied with nutrients and removed wastes. They grew for
three months on Earth. Then from September 16, 1996 through
January 22, 1997, some were flown aboard Mir.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that prolonged spaceflight weakens or changes
musculoskeletal tissues in the human body. But "after more than 25
years in space, we still can't explain this," Freed said. The
experiment provides a model for future cultivation of human bone,
muscle and other tissues in space, she said, which could help
scientists understand the mechanisms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
