<HEADLINE> US Oil Industry Official Opposes Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Laws prohibiting U.S.
companies from doing business with Libya, Iran and other countries
do more damage to the U.S. economy than to those at which the
sanctions are aimed, a U.S. oil industry official said.
</P>
<P>
"The net outcome is that the United States is restricted from
competing around the world," the local newspaper Journal of
Commerce today quoted American Petroleum Institute chief executive
Red Cavaney as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have a "quantifiable impact that directly relates
to U.S. jobs and revenues," Cavaney told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The official said the sanction policy sends a warning to other
nations that the U.S. "may not be a reliable business partner for
the future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
