<HEADLINE> US Denies Bilateral Contacts With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States has been
having quiet negotiations with Iran on ways of ending the Afghan
civil war, the Washington Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the move indicated a breach of the U.S.
long-standing policy of containing Iran.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley confirmed that
Washington had participated in meetings that the Iranians had also
attended at the United Nations over the issue of the Afghan civil
war.
</P>
<P>
But he denied it was a departure from the U.S. existing policy
toward Iran, saying, "We both belong to the United Nations and
would ordinarily find ourselves in the course of work present in
the same room."
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States attended meetings because it
supported U.N. Special Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi's initiative to find
ways to bring peace to Afghanistan, and it was nothing to do with
bilateral relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"This is a completely separate issue... about bilateral
contacts" with Iran, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Washington Times, under the auspices of the
United Nations, ambassadors from the United States, Russia, China,
Pakistan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekestan and Tajikstan and Iran held
three rounds of talks in New York on the issue of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
With regards to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's call for
dialogue with the American people, Foley said the United States
welcomed the remarks.
</P>
<P>
"We have welcomed the new tone we have begun to hear from the
Iranian president," he said. "We regard the remarks... as a
positive statement."
</P>
<P>
Foley repeated three issues, President Clinton defined earlier
today as the basis for any possible dialogues, which he said were
"support for terrorism, sponsorship of violent opposition to the
Middle East peace process and efforts to acquire weapons of mass
destruction," which the Iranian government has repeatedly denied.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry also said the Clinton
administration welcomed the remarks by President Khatami, saying
"we consider them having been made in a positive way." 
</P>
</TEXT>
