<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans Season Visit to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will make a visit to American troops in Bosnia next week, and to
make a case for keeping some forces there beyond the June
withdrawal deadline.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to leave Sunday and most likely go to Tuzla
and Sarajevo Monday to meet U.S. troops and leaders of the Bosnian
federation government, White House spokesman Michael McCurry said
today.
</P>
<P>
The president will be on ground for 12 to 14 hours. He will
give a speech in Sarajevo declaring that an international force
will probably be needed in Bosnia on a "continuing basis,"
officials said. Details of the trip are yet to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
"It's a chance to highlight what's been done and to make people
realize that we have made a real contribution there," a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
"The main thing I'm doing is going to Bosnia to thank the
American military personnel for being there and for spending their
Christmas there and for the sacrifices they've made to bring peace
to Bosnia and to tell them why it's important," Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Stabilization Force (SFOR), including 8,000 American
troops, is scheduled to leave Bosnia next June, but Washington and
its allies are considering a follow-on force beyond the deadline.
</P>
<P>
"The president has been with his advisors, thinking about the
future of Bosnia, thinking how much better positioned the future
will be because of the current Stabilization Force mission that's
deployed there," said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman told reporters that no decision has been
made on whether to extend the U.S. mission in Bosnia. But he
reaffirmed that there is "a developing consensus" that an
international presence should be in Bosnia beyond June next year.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been caught between pressure
from Congress wanting a timely pullout and Europeans saying peace
will collapse if all the troops get out.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also visited U.S. troops in Bosnia in January 1996. The
president traditionally makes an appearance with military
personnel during holiday seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
