<HEADLINE> Jordan's Government Wins Confidence in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government today
won confidence with 51 votes in favor in the 80-member newly-formed
Lower House of Parliament after two-day debate.
</P>
<P>
The 51 members were from pro-government parties and tribes,
Jordan's official news agency, Petra, reported, adding that 15
members voting against were independent Islamists, nationalists
and leftists.
</P>
<P>
Twelve members of the 78 members present abstained in the vote,
Seven of whom were ex-cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
During a speech after the vote, Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali said that his government would carry out the king Hussein's
directives and serve the whole kingdom in its best way.
</P>
<P>
Amid the discussion, more than 20 members criticized the
government for normalizing ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Most of the members pressed the government to side with Arab
countries, especially the Palestine, Syria, Iraq and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The current government was appointed in March this year to
supervise the parliamentary election in November.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties and professional associations boycotted the
election and accused it of irregularities, a charge firmly
denied by the government.
</P>
<P>
After the election, King Hussein said in a letter to Majali
that he had full confidence in his prime minister who signed the
1994 Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty during his first term as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Majali was expected to reshuffle his cabinet to include 12
new members, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
