<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Unlikely to Delay New Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp., the world's
software giant, is unlikely to delay any products or lose much in
the way of short-term profit because of last week's preliminary
ruling by the U.S. District Judge, the Wall Street Journal
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ruling, in response to a lawsuit by the Justice Department,
prohibits Microsoft from forcing personal-computer makers to
bundle Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser with any Microsoft
operating systems, including the coming version called Windows 98.
That product, which tightly integrates the browser technology is
expected to generate roughly 3 billion U.S. dollars in revenue in
its first two years and is the issue of most concern to investors.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that the ruling would prevent Microsoft
from issuing Windows 98 and Windows NT 5.0 in schedule.
</P>
<P>
But on Friday, a Justice official said the agency would be
satisfied if Microsoft offers a simple and economical way for PC
makers to delete Internet Explorer, even if the product is
shipped together with the current Windows 95 or with Windows 98,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Such a move would give PC makers a choice between Microsoft's
product and Netscape Communications Corp.'s browser, which is
rapidly losing market share, it said.
</P>
<P>
But most manufacturers, including Compaq Computer Corp.,
Hewlett-Packard Co., Dell Computer Corp. and Packard Bell NEC,
said they plan to keep using Internet Explorer along with
Microsoft's operating systems. For one thing, the Microsoft
browser is free, while Netscape charges them an estimated 1 U.S.
dollar to 10 U.S. dollars a copy for its browser.
</P>
<P>
A Microsoft spokesman said that it is still studying whether to
appeal the ruling, but the company believes the preliminary ruling
shouldn't cause it to delay the shipment next spring of Windows 98
in any case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Airlines to Equip New Ground Warning Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. airlines announced
today that they are installing improved warning systems on their
planes to caution pilots when they approach mountains or are too
close to the ground.
</P>
<P>
The "enhanced ground proximity warning systems" are already in
use in 175 airliners, and will be installed in some 4,300 more by
2003, said Carol B. Hallett, head of the Air Transport
Association.
</P>
<P>
The systems combine a massive worldwide database of terrain
with a Global Positioning System that tracks an aircraft's
position using a set of satellites.
</P>
<P>
The systems calculate the plane's position with great accuracy
and compare that position, altitude and course with the terrain
data to determine if any hazards are nearby.
</P>
<P>
The new systems can issue an advisory of approaching terrain 11
to 16 kilometers ahead. At about 6 kilometers it provides a yellow
display on a screen with an audible warning "caution, terrain,"
and at about 3 kilometers the screen turns red and the voice says
"terrain, pull up."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration is planning to require
all domestic airlines and foreign planes flying to the United
States to install the systems.
</P>
<P>
Currently, ground warning systems use a plane's radar to detect
when the ground is too close and warn the pilot to pull up.
However, in some cases the warming was too late for a pilot to
have enough time to recover.
</P>
<P>
A Korean Air Boeing 747 struck high ground and crashed on
landing approach in Guam last August, killing all 226 people
aboard and in December 1995 an American Airlines Boeing 757 struck
a mountainside in Colombia, killing all but four of the 163
aboard.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 10 years there have been 36 crashes killing 2,400
people worldwide that were classified as "controlled flight into
terrain." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Not to Execute Fifth Jordanian: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has informed Jordan
officially that the fifth Jordanian man sentenced to death on
charge of smuggling car parts will not be executed, officials of
the Jordanian Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision was conveyed by Iraqi Ambassador to Jordan
Nouri Elwayess to Jordanian Secretary-General of Foreign Ministry
Ibrahim Nagawi during a meeting held Sunday, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to spare Ammar Ghaleb Shehabeddine's life came
after Jordan expelled seven Iraqi diplomats in retaliation for
Iraq's execution of four Jordanians last Monday on the same
charge.
</P>
<P>
Car parts are in short supply in Iraq due to the U.N.-imposed
sanctions against its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The seven Iraqi diplomats expelled are scheduled to leave Amman
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iraq used to be firm allies before and during the
Gulf crisis. However their bilateral ties suffered setbacks after
the Gulf war as Jordan was eager to distance itself from Iraq to
end international alienation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
