<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader: Talks on Cyprus Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Northern Cyprus leader Ruaf
Denktash said today that the intercommunal talks between Turkish
and Greek Cypriots have been killed by the European Union (EU), the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported from Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Tenktash said that the idea of federation is no more at the
agenda after the EU decided to start full membership negotiations
with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Denktash as saying that northern Cyprus will
not hold contacts with the United Nations regarding the
intercommunal talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriots,
adding: "EU Representative to Cyprus Jilles Anouil's mission has
come to an end in northern Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
He said, "The Greek Cypriot side tries to claim responsibility
over Cyprus by ignoring the rights of the Turkish community. There
are two states in Cyprus and they have to set up good neighborhood
relations and respect each other's rights, so that they can open
the way for re-unification."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, Denktash added, "Those who accept
our state will come and meet us, and it is just a waste of time
to meet those who do not recognize our state."
</P>
<P>
The EU summit held on December 12-13 in Luxembourg decided
to start negotiations with five central and eastern European
countries--Estonia, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Slovenia--as well as Cyprus from next spring on the adhesion
of these countries to the union.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into a southern Greek Cypriot community
and a northern Turkish Cypriot community in 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
Mediterranean island after an abortive pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been making efforts to seek
a solution to the protracted problem, but no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Russia Opens New Page in Ties: Yilmaz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz said here today that Turkey and Russia agreed to refrain
from behaviors and attitudes which could threaten the economic
interests and territorial integrity of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the remark at a joint press conference with his
Russian counterpart Victor Chernomyrdin following three-hour-long
talks and a signing ceremony of several agreements between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said that his talks on bilateral relations, regional
and international issues with Chernomyrdin, who arrived in Ankara
this morning for a two-day official visit, were "very useful."
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have shared the same points of view to make joint
efforts in developing our economic and trade cooperation as well
as our political relations."
</P>
<P>
He believed that the signed agreements will open a new page in
Turkish-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said that he had accepted the invitation by
Chernomyrdin to pay a visit to Moscow in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Chernomyrdin said their signed agreements would
enhance bilateral relations, adding that through his contacts with
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and high-ranking officials,
Russia and Turkey have established a basis for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Under one of the signed agreements, the two countries will join
efforts in the construction of a natural gas pipeline from Russia
to Turkey via under the black sea.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is expected to invest 3.3 billion dollars in the
project, which involves increasing the capacity of an existing
pipeline through Ukraine, Romania and Bulgaria as well as laying a
new one from southern Russian under the Black Sea to Turkey's
northern coast.
</P>
<P>
The undersea pipeline, known as "Blue Stream," will pass at a
depth of 2,100 meters under the Black Sea waters.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin will go to Istanbul Tuesday to attend a meeting
with businessmen and will leave Turkey Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
