<HEADLINE> France Calls for Pursuit of EU-Turkey Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- France today called for the
continuation of dialogue between the European Union (EU) and
Turkey, after Ankara cut all political dialogue with EU in protest
of its refusal to include Turkey in its enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
France also asked Britain, which will take over the presidency
of EU from January 1, 1999, to solve the problem between EU and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"For us, one should continue the dialogue between EU and
Ankara, and we count on the future British presidency to take the
appropriate initiatives in this regard," said French Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit held on December 12-13 in Luxembourg decided to
start negotiations with five central and eastern European
countries -- Estonia, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Slovenia -- as well as Cyprus from next Spring on the adhesion by
these countries into the union.
</P>
<P>
Turkey protested the EU decision and announced the cutting of
political dialogue with EU, the boycott of the EU conferences, and
the continuation of "integration" of the northern part of Cyprus
with Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
