<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Chief of Staff Visits Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi arrived here this evening on a four-day
visit to Egypt at the invitation of his Egyptian counterpat
General Magdi Hatatah.
</P>
<P>
He will have talks with senior Egyptian military officials on
means of boosting military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries at the just-concluded Islamic summit in Tehran
had been critical of Turkey's controversial defense cooperation
with Israel. President Suleyman Demirel withdrew from the meeting
one day ahead of schedule to avoid facing concerted bombardment.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has joined these countries in voicing grave concern over
the rapidly growing military ties between Ankara and Tel Aviv. The
alliance was capped by a three-day visit by Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai to Ankara early this month.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular state,
has said that its move to develop military cooperation with Israel
will not produce negative impact on its friendship with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed two defense and military training
agreements last year to allow joint warplanes exercises in each
other's airspace and use Israel's technology to update Turkey's
tanks and missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
