<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Set to Ban EU Beef Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- British Agriculture Minister
Jack Cunningham said today the government was set to ban all beef
imports from Europe which fail to meet British health standards.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a decision by EU veterinary experts earlier
today to delay the introduction of new anti-BSE controls at
abattoirs across Europe for three months.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham told BBC radio he would table orders in parliament
this week "to ensure that no beef comes into Britain from January
1 unless it has been subjected to the same rigorous standards as
our own beef."
</P>
<P>
"We took this decision quite properly in July in the council of
agriculture ministers. There was a Commission decision which was
effectively EU law," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to implement it unilaterally on behalf of the
United Kingdom to make sure beef coming in is as safe as the beef
we have at home," he added.
</P>
<P>
The British government is under heavy pressure from farmers
because of low beef prices, largely due to the continuing EU ban
on exports of British beef.
</P>
<P>
The EU could no longer justify its ban on UK beef exports, he
stressed. The ban was imposed by the EU in March of last year
after the existence of mad cow disease was announced by the
British government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
