<HEADLINE> UK's Butchers Petition Parliament over Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Angry butchers presented a
petition to parliament today in a last ditch bid to stop the
government from banning sales of beef on the bone.
</P>
<P>
The petition was signed by 100,000 consumers wanting T-bone
steaks, ribs and oxtails to remain in their dinner tables. The
government decided last week to ban the beef on the bone for fear
of mad cow disease. The order will come into effect on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Federation of Meat and Food Traders Chairman, John
Fuller, told reporters the number of signatories was "very
encouraging," especially given the short space of time available
to arrange it.
</P>
<P>
The conservative MP, Bill Cash, who supported the protest, said
the new order to ban the bone beef was panic measure which
undermined confidence in British beef and meat producers'
livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham is
meeting fellow European Union agriculture ministers in Brussels to
discuss plans to lift the ban on British beef exports which was
imposed by the EU in March 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
