<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Diabetes Cases Forecast to Double by 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of diabetes cases in
the world is forecast to nearly double to reach 220 million by the
year 2010, according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The report by the British Diabetic Association (BDA) said that
in 1995 the number of people with the illness was estimated at 123
million, but over the next 13 years, the cases will increase
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
It said that the main reason for the rise is a rapid change in
lifestyle and population demography, with growing obesity,
Western-style diets, less physical exercise and a rising elderly
population all contributing.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that in Asia and Africa diabetes could
become two to three times more common than it is now, and by 2010,
it is forecast that Asia will be home to 61 percent of the total
global number of people with diabetes.
</P>
<P>
Paul Zimmet, one of the authors of the report, said that "with
the unrestrained forces of economic globalization and
industrialization, the prevalence of diabetes is likely to
dramatically increase in the next millennium".
</P>
<P>
He added that the corresponding burden of complications and
premature mortality resulting from diabetes will constitute a
major public health problem for most countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baimler-Benz, Ford, Ballard To Join Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Daimler-Benz AG of Germany,
Ford Motor Company of the United States and Ballard Power Systems
of Canada announced today that they would pool their resources and
know-hows to accelerate the development of fuel-cell technology to
power future vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The three companies signed a memorandum of understanding today
in Stuttgart, Germany, with the expectation that final agreement
will be reached within a few months.
</P>
<P>
With the agreement, Ford would participate in the existing
partnership between Daimler-Benz and the Canadian company which is
the world leader in the development of proton exchange membrane
fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
Fuel cells, which generate electricity from hydrogen and oxygen
to power vehicles, have the potential to provide the size, range,
roominess and speed of conventional cars and trucks while emitting
almost only water vapor into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
With the new alliance, the three companies aim to bring to
market the first complete fuel-cell system for vehicles by the
year 2004.
</P>
<P>
"This cooperation is an impressive evidence of the fact that
the fuel cell represents a serious and promising alternative to
the conventional combustion engine," said Daimler-Benz leader
Juergen Schrempp today in Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
Ford Chairman Alex Trotman also said: "With our collaborative
efforts, we think we can accelerate the commercial viability and
implementation of fuel cell vehicles."
</P>
<P>
Ford is planning to invest about 420 million U.S. dollars in
the joint project. Daimler-Benz and Ballard are expected to put a
combined investment of more than 331 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
