<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investments Injected Into Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- More foreign investments have
been injected into Uganda, The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two foreign independent power companies -- Ugandan/American
Joint Nile Independent Power Limited (NIP) and the Arab
International Construction (U) Limited from Egypt, are the new
licensed to linvest more than one billion U.S. dollars in
generation of electrict power on Nile river, Uganda Investment
Authority (UIA) announced in its bimonthly report. The first one
will invest 400 milllion, and the second will inject 600 million
U.S. dollars and they will create 1,442 jobs in completion, the
UIA added.
</P>
<P>
The total licensed projects from July 1991 to October 1997
reached 2,316 with planned investment of 4,848 billion and will
create 159,180 jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of abolishing tax holidays for certain investments
and replacing them with depreciation allowances in June 1997,
foreign investment enthusiasm loomed, William Muhairwe, UIA
agricultural executive director, commented, introducing the
report yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The country registeredd in September and Octover a significant
increasing number of investors applying for new licences,
especially among Asian multinational companies, he added.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo Corporation of South Korea, following its campatriot of
Hyundai Corporation in August 1997, is investigating recently the
potential opportunities in power and telecommunications sector in
the country, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Three Malaisian companies also sent their teams to the country
in the same period for the same purpose, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The other major licensed projects in September and October
this year include a Uganda/British firm which is to invest 1.2
million U.S. dollars in fruit and milk processing, Iron Wood (U)
Limited, an Irish/Ugandan company to invest 6.1 million U.S.
dollars in saw milling and furniture, Aliyzeci Ubdystries
Limited, an Ethiopian firm to invest 0.789 million dollars in
extraction of essential oils, and a South African/Ugandan
company, Metro Cash and Carry (U) Limited to invest 16 million
U.S. dollars in cash and carry wholesale.
</P>
<P>
England is the leading licensed investing country during
September and October with 13 projects, followed by India with
seven projects and Ethiopia with six projects. The other
investing countries are Kenya, Somalia and South Korea with four,
Iran, Pakistan and Tanzania with three, South Africa and France
with two, U.S.A., Italy, Canada and Ireland with one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Claim 167 Lives Since December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite South African
traffic authorities's effort to stem the high number of deaths on
roads during the festive season, accidents have already claimed
the lives of 167 since the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
In one of the worst accidents, nine people were killed when a
minibus taxi was involved in a head-on collision with two other
cars at Cambridge, near East London, in Eastern Cape Province on
Saturday, Arrive Alive Information Center (AAIC) spokesman Joshua
Raborifi said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Raborifi said that road accidents have claimed the lives of
1,084 people since October this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the AAIC was appealing to pedestrians to be cautious
when crossing traffic lines and to wear bright colored clothes
when walking at night.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-six pedestrians had been killed since December 1.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is believed to be the kingdom of automobiles in
Africa. However, the developed and busy traffic have also
resulted in heavy casualties throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Major contributory factors to the high number of casualties
were related to overspeeding, driving under the influence of
alcohol, not wearing seatbelts and fatigue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Urged to Curb Official Privileges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
been urged to take measures to drastically curtail the
extravagant lifestyle of government officials which is
undermining the national economy.
</P>
<P>
In a front-page story today, the official newspaper New
Nigerian quoted National Economic Intelligence Committee Chairman
Sam Aluko as complaining that "their consumption habit only helps
to boost the economies of other nations where our wealth is
repatriated".
</P>
<P>
Slamming such wasteful privileges, Aluko said the proficiency
of public officers showed in their long fleet of cars, number of
hours and the size of estacodes, which are the allowances given
to them for their travel outside the country.
</P>
<P>
All these are maintained at the public expenses, according to
the chairman, whose committee is a government agency mandated to
supervise the country's economic activities and give consequent
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the former Zaire, Nigeria had the highest estacode
in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even the United Nations doesn't pay as much as the over 360
U.S. dollars a night which Nigeria pays its officials!" Aluko
told a recent New Nigerian forum.
</P>
<P>
"A situation where ministers travel out with more than 200,000
dollars as estacode is not obtainable even in the most developed
economies of the world," he said, adding that available records
show that the highest amount the United States and United Nations
pay officials is about 180 dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
The chairman cited his committee's discovery, saying that what
public officials spent on "invisible services" in the first
quarter of this year alone was equal to the spending on similar
services throughout last year.
</P>
<P>
He wondered how the budget deficit could be curtailed if such
attitude persisted.
</P>
<P>
Aluko also condemned the practice of travelling out with a
retinue of officials, "including some members of the press who
only come back to sing the praises of the officials".
</P>
<P>
The flamboyance of the public officers only adds to the drain
on the country's resources, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"If we plug some of the leaks in the system, we will be one of
the richest in the world," the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
He thus suggested drastic curtailment of official privileges,
saying that public officials should use their own cars and be
made to pay their rents.
</P>
<P>
"With the exception of the head of state and the chief of
general staff who should be accorded all the protocol and
privileges of office, all other public officials should pay their
rents and telephones," Aluko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
