<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Form New Cabinet within Two Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's military leader
General Sani Abacha will form a new cabinet by the end of this
month, a senior military leader has said.
</P>
<P>
Rear Admiral Mike Akhigbe, chief of the naval staff, made the
assurance on Sunday while paying a visit to the Bayelsa State
Administrator, Navy Captain Omonyi Caleb Olubolade.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe, who was there to endorse the list of the executive
council (cabinet) nominees submitted by the state, explained that
the presidency is taking its time in screening the nominees,
especially as the transition to civil rule program is now at a
critical stage.
</P>
<P>
General Abacha sacked his cabinet on November 17, the fourth
anniversary of his leadership. He explained that this was
necessary to ensure the success of the transition program and to
allow some cabinet members to contest in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Three ministers were immediately renamed, which included
Financial Minister Anthony Ani, Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi and
Lieutenant-General Jeremiah Useni, Minister of the Federal
Capital Territory. But the delay in naming other cabinet members
has caused wide concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971216.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mbeki Will Make S. Africa Prosperous: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
has expressed confidence in his deputy Thabo Mbeki as his
successor to lead South Africa into prosperity as both president
of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) and of the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Sunday, Mandela said Mbeki was a man
of "exceptional qualities who would put the ANC at a level that
it has never reached before", adding that "Unlike me he is a
diplomat."
</P>
<P>
Mandela will step down as president of the ANC at the party's
annual congress due to be started Tuesday in Mafiken, capital of
North West Province. Mbeki is the sole candidate for the
position.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has also put his stamp of approval on the current ANC
national chairman Jocob Zuma's candidacy for the deputy
presidency of the ANC. Zuma was an "absolutely outstanding
leader," Mandela noted.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that the 50th ANC national conference
is crucial to the transformation process that will take South
Africa into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the five-day meeting would offer the ANC a chance
to reflect on the party's achievements and drawbacks since it
came to power in the 1994 general elections.
</P>
<P>
In addition to setting up the party's new leadership, more
than 3,000 delegates will also discuss other important issues,
including economic and social transformation, the role of the
state and governance, peace and stability as well as
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
They will also work out strategy to prepare for the 1999
national elections without Mandela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
