<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Another Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia launched another
military satellite of its series into orbit from the Plesetsk
launching site in northern Russia at 18:40 local time on Monday,
according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The satellite belongs to the Yantar subseries of the Kosmos
series. Fitted with photographic equipment, Yantars are used to
monitor international accords to limit or reduce armaments.
</P>
<P>
Yantars, which are developed by the Central Socialized Design
Bureau in Samara, have undergone at least two upgrades since the
first Yantar went into space in December 1974.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s the Soviet Union launched six or seven
Yantars a year. This made possible practically continuous
monitoring since each satellite stayed in orbit for 55 to 59 days,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, because of recent financial problems, Russia launched
only two satellites in 1994, another two in 1995 and only one last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
