<HEADLINE> Nigeria's State Assembly Election Sparks Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The National Centre Party of
Nigeria (NCPN) has rejected the results of last Saturday's state
assembly election and threatened to reconsider its participation
in the military government's transition to civil rule program,
media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
NCPN is the second of Nigeria's five political parties that
has voiced their protest over the election, which saw a landslide
victory for the United Nigeria Congress Party (UNCP).
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party of Nigeria (DPN), which came the second
in the election, Friday threatened to return its registration
certificate to the government in a protest over alleged
manipulation of the election.
</P>
<P>
The party is reportedly under pressure from its state chairman
to boycott the rest of the transition program.
</P>
<P>
The NCPN's decision was made at a national caucus held at the
weekend in Abuja to review the election.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued after the meeting and signed by its
national chairman Magaji Abdullahi said the NCPN "observed with
regret that the outcome of the elections during this transition
period has become so manifestly predictable and lopsided in favor
of one of the five political parties."
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the party has decided to hold a national
consultative forum Thursday in Abuja "to review its position and
participation in the rest of the elections during the transition
program".
</P>
<P>
In a related development, reports said the Transition
Implementation Committee will meet in Abuja today to hear the
report of its members who has monitored the election.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to discuss the latest development
after the election and to make its recommendations to the
government, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
