<HEADLINE> Development-Oriented Aid Programs Launched in N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Development-oriented schemes
have been launched in north Uganda to help the displaced and
jobless, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
The schemes include a World Food Program (WFP)-sponsored food
aid to the displaced in the northern districts of Kitgum and Gulu
and other employment and income generating activities such as
various construction schemes and farming projects.
</P>
<P>
The areas are those harassed by the rebel Lord's Resistance
Army (LRA) fighting against the government of President Yoweri
Museveni for some 11 years.
</P>
<P>
A WFP news release said the agency will distribute 21,044
metric tons of food worth of 13 billions of Uganda Shillings
(some 13 million U.S. dollars) to benefit 260,000 displaced
people in the areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government, non-government organisations and U.N.
agencies and the displaced people are all in favour of the
food-for-works schemes, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said some former rebels surrendering to the
government have asked the government for money or jobs, but the
local authorities have failed to meet their demands due to lack
of money or positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
