<HEADLINE> Switzerland Extends 54-m-Dollar Loan to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Switzerland today
signed an agreement to secure a loan of 80 million Swiss francs
(some 54.75 million U.S. dollars) to Egypt for development
projects, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Egyptian Minister of State for
Planning and International Cooperation Zafer el-Beshri, and,
representatives of the Swiss Federation Council and the Swiss
Banking Group.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be extended to Egypt in two phases - the first 40
million Swiss francs will be presented as a grant, the remaining
40 million francs as soft credits from Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
The money will be channeled for development programs such as
the setting up of blood banks, water pumps in southern Egypt, and
electricity projects.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a Swiss representative after the signing
ceremony as saying that the agreement showed his government's
keenness to maintain cooperation with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The November 17 "regrettable" terrorist attack that killed over
30 Swiss nationals will not affect the traditional relationship
between Swiss and Egyptian peoples but will rather provide an
incentive for them to face up to such crimes with strength and
determination, he said.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Switzerland, Britain, Japan and Scandinavian
countries discouraged their citizens from travelling to Egypt on
the heels of the Luxor massacre which killed 58 foreign tourists
and four Egyptians last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
