<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Appeals to Consider Three Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) said today that political will and
financial support are needed to solve three principal
environmental problems in the next century.
</P>
<P>
A biennial report for 1996-1997 issued here today by the UNEP
Secretariat said action to safeguard the planet's limited
freshwater resources, continued momentum to protect the oceans
and an environmentally sustainable global energy strategy need
more than urgent consideration in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
As the world's freshwater resources are both finite and
irreplaceable, the report said, wider inter-governmental dialogue
on fresh water is now long overdue if the most vital of natural
resources are to be preserved.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the unique "fair share" approach currently being
pioneered in Africa should serve as a model for the wider
international community.
</P>
<P>
The approach, based on environmental protection, economic
development and social equality, is designed to ensure adequate
and clean water supplies for all.
</P>
<P>
On the protection of the oceans, the report pointed out, a
Global Program of Action for the Protection of the Marine
Environment from Land-based Activities is being negotiated.
</P>
<P>
As 1998 marks the International Year of the Ocean, the world
community needs to think about the inter-relationships between
new action on the oceans, the UNEP regional seas programs, the
International Law of the Sea and the urgent need for
environmentally sustainable fisheries management.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the global energy strategy, the report noted that
energy is a key to development but at present its by-products are
the main drivers of global warming, damaging the air quality in
cities and polluting the oceans.
</P>
<P>
It stated that UNEP should enhance its work in the field of
cleaner industrial production and at the same time continue to
test environmentally sound technologies and share the results
through a clearing-house.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, "to date no environmental issue has
emerged which is beyond the capacity of humankind to resolve."
</P>
<P>
In order to tap this human ingenuity, the report said, UNEP
should above all build the will to affect environmentally
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
In the view of the report, "the strongest weapon available to
environmentalists is an informed and concerned civil society."
</P>
<P>
UNEP will continue to promote changes in lifestyle, enabling
world citizens to understand that "their daily choices are, in
the end, what will decide the future of the planet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
