<HEADLINE> Fast Train Delayed on Second Day of Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The 300-kilometer fast train
service starting from Brussels was delayed today on the second day
of its inauguration due to a strike waged by train conductors.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing trains were delayed by some 30 minutes, according to
local television RTBF reports.
</P>
<P>
The commercial service, known as Thalys and started on Sunday,
linked Brussels with Paris, Amsterdam and Cologne with greatly
reduced travel times.
</P>
<P>
The delay was caused by the strike after SNCF, the French
national railroad company, refused to reconsider the claims by
train conductors to have their pays raised.
</P>
<P>
The strike came unexpected as the fast train service was
inaugurated grandiosely by Belgian King Albert II and Queen Paola
last Wednesday first in Belgium and then in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The fast train service, with departures every hour in each
direction, cut the travel time from Brussels to Paris by more than
half an hour to one hour 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
It is hailed by the European Union as a showcase of its
improvement of the single market infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The upgrading of the train is part of a collaboration among
Belgium, France, the Netherlands and Germany to overcome national
borders and make the train competitive with air travel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
