<HEADLINE> 60 S.Leonean Refugees Feared Drowned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- About 60 fleeing Sierra Leonean
refugees were feared dead after the canoe they were using to
cross the Mano River to reach Liberia capsized over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The independent star radio in monrovia, capital of liberia,
today quoted one of the survivors as reporting that the victims
of th weekend tragidy are mostly women and children, who seemed
screaming for help after the canoe overturned.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were fleeing with renewed fighting in
northeastern Sierra Leone between troops of the military junta
and traditional hunters known as Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcasting Corporation today reported that one
of the bodies of the dead had been found but it is not yet clear
whether rescue workers have managed to get to the scene of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted eyewitnesses as saying that the junta forces
had attacked the Kamajor positions at several points over the
past couple of days in eastern Sierra Leone, burning down a
number of villages.
</P>
<P>
The latest upsurging fighting has forced hundreds of Sierra
leoneans to flee across the border, swelling the liberian border
town of kango.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, jet fighters belonging to the Liberia-based west
African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG were reportedly seen
flying to the direction of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, ECOMOG warned the illegal regime in Sierra Leone
to stop its unprovoked attacks on civilians or face consequences
of its actions. 
</P>
