<HEADLINE> S. Africa Makes Headway in Sugar Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South African sugar
production has increased in the 1996/97 season, according to a latest
survey by the South African Sugar Association.
</P>
<P>
Th survey shows that in the 1996/97 season, 2.2 million tons
of sugar was produced by the country's 47,000 growers. Of this,
1.2 millions was consumed domestically and 995,630 tons exported.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings for the season were worth 229 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is indicated that the 1997/98 season is likely to produce a
bigger crop -- about 2.4 million tons, and that sugar export earning
will rise above the 1996/97 level.
</P>
<P>
The past season was the best one experienced by the local sugar
industry in the past decade and ended a run of five consecutive poor
seasons.
</P>
<P>
Mainly due to drought, South Africa exported just 123,173 tons of
sugar in 1992/93, nothing in 1993/94, 347,507 tons in 1994/95, and
375,653 tons in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
South African sugar exports in 1997/98 are expected to exceed one
million tons, the industry sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
