<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Southern African Intergrated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A two-day conference on
intergrated development in southern Africa opened in Chinhoyi,
north Zimbabwe today, urging countries in the region to support a
new form of regional collaboration which is people oriented and
encourages genuine development.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Chairman of the Zimbabwe Intergrated
Program (ZIP) Heneri Dzinotyiweyi said the governments in the
region should adopt policies that were people centered, eradicate
poverty and promote a compatible educational system which aims at
promoting regional collaboration among people at the grassroots
level.
</P>
<P>
''The history of collaboration is largely apparent at the
levels of heads of states and the governments through such
organisations as the Southern African Development Community
(SADC),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The governments, he said, must mostly ensure that poverty
eradication and full employment are achieved as that will improve
opportunities for people to interact.
</P>
<P>
The conference, being attended by more than 100
representatives from Botswana, Zambia and the Democratic Republic
of Congo will discuss, among other things, the prevailing low
income levels and poverty, constraints to regional intergration
and the severe deterioration of national economies.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches, the participants agreed that while
intergrated development in the region could be persued by the
governments and institutions, the governments should draw their
policies mandate from regional collaborative processes to realise
genuine intergrated development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
