<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 21 Lives in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 15 (Xinhua)-- More than 21 people mainly
children died from cholera in Mogadishu in the past three days,
according to figures from local health posts.
</P>
<P>
Six children and four adults have died in Medina and Bulo
Hubey areas in southwestern Mogadishu in the past 48 hours. Six
more others died in Daynille District in south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in main hospitals of the capital spoke about an
increasing deaths for the disease. The doctors said more than 40
fall down for the disease daily.
</P>
<P>
The doctors attributed the out-break of the disease to the bad
weather and the very poor sanitation in the capital which is
worsened by the rain waters.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the southern port town of Merca said that six
people have died from the disease since Friday while more than
123 others are currently under going treatment in Merca's main
hospital for the disease.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdinasir Abdi Arush, head of the Italian aid
agency, COSV, which runs the hospital, his agency has opened a
new quarantine in a former school in the town where the patients
are bing hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Arush said the new quarantine receives an average of 22
patients per day who are all suffering from cholera.
</P>
<P>
The COSV administration which receives some help from the
United Nations World Health Organization (WHO) said it is are now
running short of the supplies such as the antibiotics and
infusions.
</P>
<P>
Ten people are also reported to have died from severe
diarrhoea in the town of Tiegloow in Bakol region. Elders from
the town said 38 more people are in serious condition for the
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
