<HEADLINE> Mozambique GDP Estimated to Rise by 6.6% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 15 (Xinhu) -- Mozambique'se gross domestic
product of Mozambique in 1997 is estimated to increase by 6.6
percent, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Pascoal Mocumbi, Prime Minister of Mozambique said at
parliament after he handed over the 1998 economic and social
planning report that the average inflation from January to
November this year stands at 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rate between the Mozambican currency, Metiais, and U.S.
Dollar is basically stable, Mocumbi said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the Agriculture and Animal
Husbandry department has managed to raise its production at 5.9
percent. The 1997/98 grain shortage is estimated at 200,000 tons,
20 percent less than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
By September, the agricultural products purchase (except of
cashew) increased by 13 percent in comparision with the same
period of last year. Industry and fish production increased by
9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The construction industry has managed a rise of seven percent,
Mocumbi said.
</P>
<P>
He said tht this year's export is estimated to reach between
210- 230 million U.S.Dollars, much less than the 276 million
dollars in schedule due to the low yield of cashew production.
</P>
</TEXT>
