<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM: Turkey's Reaction to EU Decision Unwise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioanuis Kasoulides said here today that Turkey's reaction to the
European Union's (EU) decision to exclude Turkey from enlargement
process is not wise.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Kasoulides said the EU decision is
historic for Europe as well as for Cyprus. "We are fully
satisfied because the decision officially reaffirms the EU
commitment of March 1995 to begin accession talks six months
after the end of the Intergovernmental Conference," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that if Turkey accepts the European
principles, then this would provide the framework for a Cyprus
solution and good neighborly relations.
</P>
<P>
"A positive response on the part of Turkey would contribute
toward conditions of security and stability in the region,"
Kasoulides added.
</P>
<P>
On Turkey's threats to annex the northern part of Cyprus, he
said Cyprus and Greece will deal with any Turkish reaction within
international law and order.
</P>
<P>
"We are dedicated to the start of accession talks, and we
believe and expect these will begin as scheduled for March
1998," Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit decided on Saturday in Luxembourg to exclude
Turkey from the present enlargement process on grounds that it
does not meet the standard of the European bloc.
</P>
<P>
But the EU invited Turkey to attend the European Conference
scheduled to be held in Britain in March. However, the invitation
was rejected by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz announced Sunday that
Turkey will cut off its political dialogue with the EU and speed
up its integration cooperation with the Turkish Cypriots on the
Cyprus island if the EU starts accession negotiations with the
Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated South and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled North since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
