<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Call for Dialogue With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today he was "quite encouraged" by Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami's call for dialogue with the American people so as to
cover relevant issues that separate Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I was quite encouraged by Mr Khatami's statement, and it was
welcomed," Clinton told reporters during a photo session with
visiting Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
"I would like nothing better than to have a dialogue with Iran,
as long as we can have an honest discussion of the relevant
issues."
</P>
<P>
Clinton defined those issues as "sponsorship of terrorism,"
"violent attack on the Middle East peace process" and the
"development or acquisition of weapons of mass destruction," which
were categorically denied by the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
Khatami called for a "thoughtful dialogue" with the American
people in Teheran Sunday, saying, "I take this opportunity to pay
my respects to the great American people, and hope to have a
dialogue with the American people and about the United States in
the not too distant future."
</P>
<P>
His remarks were seen as the most conciliatory by an Iranian
leader toward the United States since the 1979 Islamic revolution
that led to severing of its diplomatic relations with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. official said the Clinton administration would
consider an authoritative proposal to see if it would lead to a
"positive dialogue." But he said the key to any relationship would
be changes in Iran's actions, which he did not define. 
</P>
</TEXT>
