<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Makes Progress in Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) has made significant achievements in
the implementation of the decisions adopted at the Earth Summit
held in Brazil five years ago.
</P>
<P>
A Biennial report for 1996-1997 issued here today by the UNEP
Secretariat said that with fewer resources than before, UNEP had
addressed increasing problems of environmental degradation during
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The report listed major achievements towards the
implementation of Agenda 21 adopted at the summit as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- UNEP published its first Global Environment Outlook at the
beginning of 1997, which ushers in a new era in environmental
assessment and international scientific collaboration on data
collection.
</P>
<P>
-- It has advanced a broad-based chemicals agenda to greatly
enhance the protection of the world's peoples and environment
from potentially dangerous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
--The organization has been at the forefront in the
implementation of the Vienna Convention for the Protection of the
Ozone Layer and the Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete
the Ozone Layer.
</P>
<P>
-- It has supported the launch of 188 national, sub-regional
and regional cleaner production initiatives in 61 countries as a
part of its program of sustainable production in industry.
</P>
<P>
-- It has encouraged financial services institutions to
incorporate environmental considerations into their business.
</P>
<P>
-- The organization has prepared International Technical
Guidelines for Safety in Biotechnology which were finalized and
adopted in Buenos Aires at the 1996 Conference of the Parties to
the Convention on Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the mandate for the environmental
body has been renewed and strengthened during the 1996-1997
biennium.
</P>
<P>
The special session of the U.N. General Assembly for overall
review of the implementation of Agenda 21 held in June this year
decided that UNEP should be an effective coordinator for all
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the role of UNEP in his report to the 51st U.N.
General Assembly, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that
UNEP should serve as "focal point for harmonization and
coordination of environment-related activities". 
</P>
</TEXT>
