<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Lee Civil Rights Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite Republican
opposition, U.S. President Bill Clinton named Bill Lann Lee acting
assistant attorney general for civil rights at a White House
ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
Under threat of retaliation, Clinton did so instead of making
the more controversial recess appointment that bypasses the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Republicans had blocked Lee's confirmation procedure because of
his support of affirmative action programs -- a formal effort to
provide increased employment and education opportunities for women
and ethnic minorities, to overcome past patterns of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who was also designated counselor to the attorney general
for civil rights enforcement, can serve as acting head of the
division until the end of Clinton's term.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Lee, 48, who has served since 1989 at the Legal
Defense and Educational Fund in Los Angeles of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), will
have the same authority as if he was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he will send Lee's nomination to the Senate again
early next year and he remained hopeful that after senators see
Lee in action, they will vote to confirm him.
</P>
<P>
He said he still looks forward to "to striking the word
`acting' from his title."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said there is "no one whose life story or impeccable
credentials" make him better suited for the nation's top civil
rights enforcement job."
</P>
<P>
Lee, the son of Chinese immigrants, will become the first
Asian-American to hold the civil rights position.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he made the acting appointment rather than a
recess appointment to help Lee's chances of getting confirmed
later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
