<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urges New Approaches to Solve Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today urged new approaches to be taken to solve the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan also called for
new approaches for the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities to start a sustainable process of negotiations as
early as possible.
</P>
<P>
"I remain convinced that it is essential to adopt new
approaches and ensure that the two community leaders will enter up
a continuing and sustained process of negotiations that will focus
on the preparation of the actual legal instruments that will
constitute the settlement," the secretary-general said.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan gave details of UN sponsored talks held at
Troutbeck, New York, from July 9 to 12, and at Glion, Switzerland,
from August 11 to 15, between the the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been virtually partitioned since 1974 when Turkish
troops took over the north of the island in response to a coup in
Nicosia engineered by the military junta then ruling Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
