<HEADLINE> Tajik Aircraft Crashes in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A Tajik civil plane crashed
in the United Arab Emirates tonight, killing more than 80 people,
informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, with 77 passengers and nine crew members on board
crashed in the desert 13 kilometers from Sharjah, a UAE city some
200 kilometers from the capital Abu Dhabi, the UAE's Wam news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An informed source from the Sharjah airport told Xinhua on
telephone that more than 80 people were killed and there were only
two critically-injured survivors who have been rushed to a nearby
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Saef al Hajiri, general director of the Civil
Aviation Authority in Sharjah told Wam that emergency teams have
found 55 bodies of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed two survivors, one of them is the plane's
captain, have been sent to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the plane, known as Tabolov 154 "disappeared from
radar-screen" minutes before it was ready to land at the Sharjah
airport.
</P>
<P>
He said the plane, which belongs to Tajik Air Company, took off
from the Tajik city Khugin. The flight number of the plane was not
yet available.
</P>
<P>
Television showed that the plane crashed into pieces and rescue
workers were busy collecting bodies and searching for more
survivors.
</P>
<P>
Investigation has begun into the cause of the crash and
informed sources said the Sharjah Civil Aviation Authority will
make a statement on the accident as early as Tuesday morning.
</P>
