<HEADLINE> Military Conflict With Turkey Not Possible: Greek Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos today ruled out the possibility of a military
confrontation between Greece and Turkey, saying that it was "an
ineffective way" to resolve problems.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the northern Greek city of Thessaloniki today,
Tsohatzopoulos said that if they avoided provocative actions,
showing that they were in control of whatever situation arose,
conflict was not the most effective way to resolve issues and no
reasonable person would ever suggest it.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that a conflict would be unavoidable if Turkey
tried to overturn Greece's sovereign rights in the region and
violate its national space.
</P>
<P>
The recent increase in violations of Greek airspace by Turkish
fighters would be resolved within the framework of the new NATO
structure agreed upon in Brussels last week, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new NATO structure, he said, would act as "a safety valve"
since no aircraft belonging to any member state would be able to
enter Greece's national security area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said
today that Turkey's threats, including that to annex northern
Cyprus, were seen in a negative light by the European Union and
were "a dead-end policy."
</P>
<P>
Turkey made the threats after it failed to be named candidate
for the EU membership in recent days.
</P>
<P>
As for the experts of committees set up in May by the two
countries to review their differences, the spokesman said that the
process was now frozen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
