<HEADLINE> Pentagon Announces Anthrax Vaccination for Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has decided that the American military's 1.5 million
men and women should be vaccinated against anthrax as a
preparation against germ warfare, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
The inoculations will include six shots over 18 months. About
2.4 million people will be vaccinated over a six month period
because of the movement of men and women in and out of the force,
the Pentagon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The first shots will be given this coming summer to about
100,000 soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines deployed to "high
threat" areas.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon made the decision based on America's concern of
biological or chemical warfare threat against U.S. troops at home
or overseas.
</P>
<P>
About 150,000 of the more than 500,000 U.S. troops in the Gulf
War in 1990 and 1991 were given anthrax vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine is licensed by the Food and Drug Administration and
has been in use since 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
