<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Protestant Leader Rejects Meeting With Adams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's chief
pro-British Protestant leader, David Trimble, said today he had no
intention of meeting with his rival leader Gerry Adams.
</P>
<P>
"I have no intention this week, next week, next month, so far
as one can see into the future of having a private meeting,"
Ulster Unionist (UUP) leader Trimble told reporters, scotching
speculation that he might hold talks with Adams, leader of the
Irish Republican Army's political wing Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
Trimble and his delegation are in talks with most of the
province's parties to devise ways of ending years of guerrilla
strife in Northern Ireland. But they refuse to have direct talks
with the Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair held a historic meeting with Adams
last week in Downing Street to demonstrate his wish to keep up
momentum in the search for a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards Sinn Fein leaders said the next key stage in
cementing a fragile peace must be a meeting with Trimble.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hopes of a breakthrough in the Northern Ireland
peace talks suffered a setback with another deadline passing and
no accord was reached.
</P>
<P>
The parties held their last meeting for this year today but
failed to finalize a list of key issues for next year's talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
