<HEADLINE> Tajik Aircraft Crashes in UAE, Black Box Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Sheikh Abdullah bin Mohammed
al Thani, president of Sharjah Civil Aviation Authority said
investigators have found the black box of a Tajik plane which
crashed in the United Arab Emirates (UAE) hours ago.
</P>
<P>
He said his authority will hold a press conference Tuesday
morning to "explain all aspects of the accident," in which most of
the passengers and crew, either Tajiks or Russian, have been
killed.
</P>
<P>
A Tajik governmental delegation will arrive in the UAE
Tuesday to investigate all details of the plane accident, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The plane, with 77 passengers and nine crew members on board,
crashed in the desert 13 kilometers from Sharjah, a UAE city some
200 kilometers northeast of the capital Abu Dhabi, the UAE's Wam
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An informed source from the Sharjah airport told Xinhua on
telephone that more than 80 people were killed and there were only
two critically-injured survivors who have been rushed to a nearby
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Saef al Hajiri, general director of the Civil
Aviation Authority in Sharjah told Wam that emergency teams have
found 55 bodies of the victims.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed two survivors, one of them is the plane's
captain, have been sent to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Hajiri said the plane, known as Tabolov 154 "disappeared from
radar-screen" minutes before it was ready to land at the Sharjah
airport. It crashed at 18:30 local time (1430 GMT).
</P>
<P>
He said the plane, which belongs to Tajik Air Company, took off
from Tajik city Khugin. The flight number of the plane was not yet
available.
</P>
<P>
Television showed that the plane had been reduced to pieces and
rescue workers were busy collecting bodies and searching for
survivors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
