<HEADLINE> Nyerere Calls for Economic Integration in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian former
President Julius Nyerere today called on Sub-Sahara African
leaders to unite and promote regional economic integration in a
bid to get rid of Western influence.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the international conference on "Reflections on
Leadership in Africa: 40 Years after Independence" in Dar es Salaam,
Nyerere said that African continent would develop only if its future
leaders practice self-reliance and exploit its own abundant resources
in the coming 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said that the leaders should be selective in taking the
investment to boost their economy instead of those to devastate it.
</P>
<P>
Praising South Africa as the engine of African economic
development, the veteran African politician said that most of the 53
nations in the continent were in south Sahara and were too small to
stand on their own.
</P>
<P>
"If the number of the countries is power, Africa would be one of
the most powerful continent in the world," he said. "Hence, we need
co-operation."
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference was jointly organized by the Institute of
Development Studies of the University of Dar es Salaam in collaboration
with the Nyerere Fundation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
