<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills 80 in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Death toll from cholera
has risen to 80 today as the disease killed another 20 people in
the past 24 hours, medical sources said.
</P>
<P>
The situation is getting worse as more and more people began to
contract the killer disease. A total of 35 sufferers were sent to two
cholera emergency centers at Sebleni and Magogoni this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Medical staff in the isles' largest medical institution Mnazi
Mmoja General Hospital and the two centers are running up and down in
frantic effort to save the lives of of admitted patients.
</P>
<P>
There is no space left at the hospital as all departments are
filled with patients, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Some staff were seen with loudspeakers asking people not to come
close to the quarantined wards as hundreds of relatives kept vigil
outside.
</P>
<P>
Hospital staff complained that they are short of hands to
effectively cope with the situation, especially during night when a
single nurse had to attend to more than 20 patients.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Water Ministry, Said Saleh Suleiman,
said today that Zanzibar water supply is germ free as it had always
been treated.
</P>
<P>
Most areas in downtown Zanzibar kept unusually quiet as school
remained closed while parents confined their children indoors.
</P>
<P>
People have been queuing up at several pharmacies seeking to buy
drugs like tertracycline, erythromycin, flagyl and fenegan which are
said to be very helpful in treating the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
