<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Repatriate Three Congo (K) Generals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is
considering to repatriate three former Zairean generals who had
allegedly planned to overthrow the new government of President
Laurent kabila, police said today.
</P>
<P>
Investigating officer inspector Thethiwe Ntjana said the three,
Mavua Madima, Kpama Baramoto and Ngbane Nzimbi, would be repatriated
to their country of origin, unless they applied for refugee status in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The three former generals were arrested near Johannesburg
Saturday following an extensive South African inv'4c3pwnYwto
=YZ9Pctivities.
</P>
<P>
They are being held on charges relating to entering South Africa
with illegal passports.
</P>
<P>
"We have no jurisdiction to put them on trial here," Ntjana said.
"They are prohibited persons, which means they are in the country
illegally."
</P>
<P>
Intelligence Ministry spokesman Helmut Schlenter said in Pretoria
that the probe into the three generals was launched after Kabila in
August presented the South African government with a list of names of
former Zairean military personnel who fled to South Africa after
Mobutu Sese Seko was overthrown in May. 
</P>
